# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abbeville
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The German invasion was preceded by the Danzig crisis and began on 1 September 1939, one week after the signing of the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact between Germany and the Soviet Union, and one day after the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union had approved the pact.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Soviets invaded Poland on 17 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The campaign ended on 6 October with Germany and the Soviet Union dividing the whole of Poland under the terms of the German–Soviet Frontier Treaty.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The aim of the invasion was to disestablish Poland as a sovereign country, with its citizens destined for extermination.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] German and Slovak forces invaded Poland from the north, south, and west the morning after the Gleiwitz incident.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] As the Wehrmacht advanced, Polish forces withdrew from their forward bases of operation close to the Germany–Poland border to more established defense lines to the east.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] After the mid-September Polish defeat in the Battle of the Bzura, the Germans gained an undisputed advantage.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Polish forces then withdrew to the southeast where they prepared for a long defence of the Romanian Bridgehead and awaited expected support and relief from France and the United Kingdom.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 3 September, based on their alliance agreements with Poland, the United Kingdom and France declared war on Germany; in the end their aid to Poland was very limited.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] France invaded a small part of Germany in the Saar Offensive, and the Polish army was effectively defeated even before the British Expeditionary Force could be transported to continental Europe.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 17 September, the Soviet Red Army invaded Eastern Poland, the territory beyond the Curzon Line that fell into the Soviet "sphere of influence" according to the secret protocol of the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact; this rendered the Polish plan of defence obsolete.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Facing a second front, the Polish government concluded the defence of the Romanian Bridgehead was no longer feasible and ordered an emergency evacuation of all troops to neutral Romania.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 6 October, following the Polish defeat at the Battle of Kock, German and Soviet forces gained full control over Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The success of the invasion marked the end of the Second Polish Republic, though Poland never formally surrendered.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 8 October, after an initial period of military administration, Germany directly annexed western Poland and the former Free City of Danzig and placed the remaining block of territory under the administration of the newly established General Government.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Soviet Union incorporated its newly acquired areas into its constituent Byelorussian and Ukrainian republics, and immediately started a campaign of Sovietization.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In the aftermath of the invasion, a collective of underground resistance organizations formed the Polish Underground State within the territory of the former Polish state.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Many of the military exiles who escaped Poland joined the Polish Armed Forces in the West, an armed force loyal to the Polish government-in-exile.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 30 January 1933, the National Socialist German Workers' Party, under its leader Adolf Hitler, came to power in Germany.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] As part of this long-term policy, Hitler at first pursued a policy of rapprochement with Poland, trying to improve opinion in Germany, culminating in the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact of 1934.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Earlier, Hitler's foreign policy worked to weaken ties between Poland and France and attempted to manoeuvre Poland into the Anti-Comintern Pact, forming a cooperative front against the Soviet Union.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland would be granted territory to its northeast in Ukraine and Belarus if it agreed to wage war against the Soviet Union, but the concessions the Poles were expected to make meant that their homeland would become largely dependent on Germany, functioning as little more than a client state.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Poles feared that their independence would eventually be threatened altogether; historically Hitler had already denounced the right of Poland to independence in 1930, writing that Poles and Czechs were a "rabble not worth a penny more than the inhabitants of Sudan or India.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The population of the Free City of Danzig was strongly in favour of annexation by Germany, as were many of the ethnic German inhabitants of the Polish territory that separated the German exclave of East Prussia from the rest of the Reich.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Corridor constituted land long disputed by Poland and Germany, and was inhabited by a Polish majority.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Corridor had become a part of Poland after the Treaty of Versailles.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Many Germans also wanted the urban port city of Danzig and its environs (comprising the Free City of Danzig) to be reincorporated into Germany.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Danzig city had a German majority, and had been separated from Germany after Versailles and made into the nominally independent Free City.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Hitler sought to use this as *casus belli*, a reason for war, reverse the post-1918 territorial losses, and on many occasions had appealed to German nationalism, promising to "liberate" the German minority still in the Corridor, as well as Danzig.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The invasion was referred to by Germany as the 1939 Defensive War (*Verteidigungskrieg*) since Hitler proclaimed that Poland had attacked Germany and that "Germans in Poland are persecuted with a bloody terror and are driven from their homes.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland participated with Germany in the partition of Czechoslovakia that followed the Munich Agreement, although they were not part of the agreement.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] It coerced Czechoslovakia to surrender the region of Český Těšín by issuing an ultimatum to that effect on 30 September 1938, which was accepted by Czechoslovakia on 1 October.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] This region had a Polish majority and had been disputed between Czechoslovakia and Poland in the aftermath of World War I.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish annexation of Slovak territory (several villages in the regions of Čadca, Orava and Spiš) later served as the justification for the Slovak state to join the German invasion.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] By 1937, Germany began to increase its demands for Danzig, while proposing that an extraterritorial roadway, part of the Reichsautobahn system, be built in order to connect East Prussia with Germany proper, running through the Polish Corridor.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland rejected this proposal, fearing that after accepting these demands, it would become increasingly subject to the will of Germany and eventually lose its independence as the Czechs had.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The British were also wary of Germany's increasing strength and assertiveness threatening its balance of power strategy.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 31 March 1939, Poland formed a military alliance with the United Kingdom and with France, believing that Polish independence and territorial integrity would be defended with their support if it were to be threatened by Germany.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On the other hand, British Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain and his Foreign Secretary, Lord Halifax, still hoped to strike a deal with Hitler regarding Danzig (and possibly the Polish Corridor).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Chamberlain and his supporters believed war could be avoided and hoped Germany would agree to leave the rest of Poland alone.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] German hegemony over Central Europe was also at stake.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In private, Hitler said in May that Danzig was not the important issue to him, but the creation of *Lebensraum* for Germany.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] With tensions mounting, Germany turned to aggressive diplomacy.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 28 April 1939, Hitler unilaterally withdrew from both the German-Polish Non-Aggression Pact of 1934 and the Anglo-German Naval Agreement of 1935.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Talks over Danzig and the Corridor broke down, and months passed without diplomatic interaction between Germany and Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] During this interim period, the Germans learned that France and Great Britain had failed to secure an alliance with the Soviet Union against Germany, and that the Soviet Union was interested in an alliance with Germany against Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Hitler had already issued orders to prepare for a possible "solution of the Polish problem by military means" through the Case White scenario.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] With the surprise signing of the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact on 24 August, the result of secret Nazi–Soviet talks held in Moscow, Germany neutralized the possibility of Soviet opposition to a campaign against Poland and war became imminent.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The German assault was originally scheduled to begin at 4:00 a.m. on 26 August.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, on 25 August, the Polish-British Common Defence Pact was signed as an annex to the Franco-Polish alliance.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In this accord, Britain committed itself to the defence of Poland, guaranteeing to preserve Polish independence.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] At the same time, the British and the Poles were hinting to Berlin that they were willing to resume discussions—not at all how Hitler hoped to frame the conflict.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Thus, he wavered and postponed his attack until 1 September, managing to in effect halt the entire invasion "in mid-leap".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, there was one exception: during the night of 25–26 August, a German sabotage group, which had not received orders to suspend action, attacked the Jablunkov Pass and Mosty railway station in Silesia.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On the morning of 26 August, the group was repelled by Polish troops.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The German side described all this as an incident "caused by an insane individual".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 26 August, Hitler tried to dissuade the British and the French from interfering in the upcoming conflict, even pledging that the *Wehrmacht* forces would be made available to Britain's empire in the future.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The negotiations convinced Hitler that there was little chance the Western Allies would declare war on Germany, and even if they did, because of the lack of "territorial guarantees" to Poland, they would be willing to negotiate a compromise favourable to Germany after its conquest of Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Meanwhile, the increased number of overflights by high-altitude reconnaissance aircraft and cross-border troop movements signaled to all observers that war was imminent.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 29 August, prompted by the British, Germany issued one last diplomatic offer, with *Fall Weiss* yet to be rescheduled.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] That evening, the German government responded in a communication that it aimed not only for the restoration of Danzig but also the Polish Corridor (which had not previously been part of Hitler's demands) in addition to the safeguarding of the German minority in Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] It said that they were willing to commence negotiations, but indicated that a Polish representative with the power to sign an agreement had to arrive in Berlin the next day while in the meantime Germany would draw up a set of proposals.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On the night of 30/31 August, German Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop read a 16-point German proposal to ambassador Nevile Henderson.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] When the ambassador requested a copy of the proposals for transmission to the Polish government, Ribbentrop refused, on the grounds that the requested Polish representative had failed to arrive by midnight.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] When Polish Ambassador Lipski went to see Ribbentrop later, on 31 August, to indicate that Poland was favorably disposed to negotiations, he announced that he did not have the full power to sign an agreement, and Ribbentrop dismissed him.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] German radio then broadcast that Poland had rejected Germany's offer, and that, therefore, negotiations with Poland had come to an end.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Hitler issued orders for the invasion to commence soon afterwards.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 29 August, Polish Minister of Foreign Affairs Józef Beck ordered military mobilization, but under pressure from Great Britain and France, the mobilization was cancelled.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] When the final mobilization started, it added to the confusion in the country.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 30 August, the Polish Navy sent its destroyer flotilla to Britain, executing the Peking Plan.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On the same day, Marshal of Poland Edward Rydz-Śmigły announced the mobilization of Polish troops.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, he was pressured into revoking the order by the French, who apparently still hoped for a diplomatic settlement, failing to realize that the Germans were fully mobilized and concentrated at the Polish border.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] During the night of 31 August, the Gleiwitz incident, a false flag attack on the radio station, was staged near the border city of Gleiwitz in Upper Silesia by German units posing as Polish troops, as part of the wider Operation Himmler.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 31 August, Hitler ordered hostilities against Poland to start at 4:45 the next morning.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, partly because of the earlier stoppage, Poland finally managed to mobilize only about 70% of its planned forces (about 900,000 of 1,350,000 soldiers planned to mobilize in first order).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Because of that, many units were still forming or moving to their designated frontline positions.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The late mobilization reduced combat capability of the Polish Army by about 1/3.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] On 31 August, Edward VIII, the Duke of Windsor, sent a message to Victor Emmanuel III, the King of Italy, asking for Italy to intervene and try to prevent Germany and Poland from going to war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Germany had a substantial numeric advantage over Poland and had developed a significant military before the conflict.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The *Heer* (army) had 3,472 tanks in its inventory, of which 2,859 were with the Field Army and 408 with the Replacement Army.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] 453 tanks were assigned into four light divisions, while another 225 tanks were in detached regiments and companies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Most notably, the Germans had seven *Panzer* divisions, with 2,009 tanks between them, using a new operational doctrine.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] It held that these divisions should act in coordination with other elements of the military, punching holes in the enemy line and isolating selected units, which would be encircled and destroyed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] This would be followed up by less-mobile mechanized infantry and foot soldiers.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The *Luftwaffe* (air force) provided both tactical and strategic air power, particularly dive bombers that disrupted lines of supply and communications.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Together, the new methods were nicknamed "*Blitzkrieg*" (lightning war).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] While historian Basil Liddell Hart claimed "Poland was a full demonstration of the *Blitzkrieg* theory", some other historians disagree.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Aircraft played a major role in the campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Bombers also attacked cities, causing huge losses amongst the civilian population through terror bombing and strafing.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The *Luftwaffe* forces consisted of 1,180 fighters, 290 Ju 87 *Stuka* dive bombers, 1,100 conventional bombers (mainly Heinkel He 111s and Dornier Do 17s), and an assortment of 550 transport and 350 reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In total, Germany had close to 4,000 aircraft, most of them modern.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] A force of 2,315 aircraft was assigned to *Weiss*.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Due to its earlier participation in the Spanish Civil War, the *Luftwaffe* was probably the most experienced, best-trained and best-equipped air force in the world in 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Emerging in 1918 as an independent country after 123 years of the Partitions of Poland, the Second Polish Republic, when compared with countries such as United Kingdom or Germany, was a relatively indigent and mostly agricultural country.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The partitioning powers did not invest in the development of industry, especially in the armaments industry in ethnically Polish areas.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Moreover, Poland had to deal with damage caused by World War I.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] This resulted in the need to build a defense industry from scratch.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Between 1936 and 1939, Poland invested heavily in the newly created Central Industrial Region.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Preparations for a defensive war with Germany were ongoing for many years, but most plans assumed fighting would not begin before 1942.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] To raise funds for industrial development, Poland sold much of the modern equipment it produced.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In 1936, a National Defence Fund was set up to collect funds necessary for strengthening the Polish Armed forces.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Army had approximately a million soldiers, but not all were mobilized by 1 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Latecomers sustained significant casualties when public transport became targets of the *Luftwaffe*.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish military had fewer armored forces than the Germans, and these units, dispersed within the infantry, were unable to effectively engage the Germans.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Experiences in the Polish–Soviet War shaped Polish Army organizational and operational doctrine.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Unlike the trench warfare of World War I, the Polish–Soviet War was a conflict in which the cavalry's mobility played a decisive role.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland acknowledged the benefits of mobility but was unable to invest heavily in many of the expensive, unproven inventions since then.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In spite of this, Polish cavalry brigades were used as mobile mounted infantry and had some successes against both German infantry and cavalry.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] An average Polish infantry division consisted of 16,492 soldiers and was equipped with 326 light and medium machine guns, 132 heavy machine guns, 92 anti-tank rifles and several dozen light, medium, heavy, anti-tank and anti-airplane field artillery.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Contrary to the 1,009 cars and trucks and 4,842 horses in the average German infantry division, the average Polish infantry division had 76 cars and trucks and 6,939 horses.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Air Force (*Lotnictwo Wojskowe*) was at a severe disadvantage against the German *Luftwaffe* due to inferiority in numbers and the obsolescence of its fighter planes.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, contrary to German propaganda, it was not destroyed on the ground—in fact it was successfully dispersed before the conflict started and not a single one of its combat planes was destroyed on the ground in the first days of the conflict.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In the era of fast progress in aviation the Polish Air Force lacked modern fighters, vastly due to the cancellation of many advanced projects, such as the PZL.38 Wilk and a delay in the introduction of a completely new modern Polish fighter PZL.50 Jastrząb.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, its pilots were among the world's best trained, as proven a year later in the Battle of Britain, in which the Poles played a notable part.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Overall, the Germans enjoyed numerical and qualitative aircraft superiority.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland had only about 600 aircraft, of which only PZL.37 Łoś heavy bombers were modern and comparable to their German counterparts.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Air Force had roughly 185 PZL P.11 and some 95 PZL P.7 fighters, 175 PZL.23 *Karaś* Bs, 35 *Karaś* as light bombers.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] However, for the September Campaign, not all of those aircraft were mobilized.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] By 1 September, out of about 120 heavy bombers PZL.37s produced, only 36 PZL.37s were deployed, the rest being mostly in training units.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] All those aircraft were of indigenous Polish design, with the bombers being more modern than the fighters, according to the Ludomił Rayski air force expansion plan, which relied on a strong bomber force.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Air Force consisted of a 'Bomber Brigade', 'Pursuit Brigade' and aircraft assigned to the various ground armies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish fighters were older than their German counterparts; the PZL P.11 fighter—produced in the early 1930s—had a top speed of only 365 km/h (227 mph), far less than German bombers.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] To compensate, the pilots relied on its maneuverability and high diving speed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Air Force's decisions to strengthen its resources came too late, mostly due to budget limitations.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] As a "last minute" order in the summer of 1939, Poland bought 160 French Morane-Saulnier M.S.406 fighters and 111 English airplanes (100 light bombers Fairey Battle, 10 Hurricanes and 1 Supermarine Spitfire; the sale of 150 Spitfires asked by the Polish government was rejected by the Air Ministry).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Despite the fact that some of the airplanes had been shipped to Poland (the first transport of purchased aircraft on the ship "Lassel" sailed from Liverpool on 28 August), none of them would take part in combat.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In late 1938, the Polish Air Force also ordered 300 advanced PZL.46 Sum light bombers, but due to a delay in starting mass production, none of them were delivered before 1 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] When in the spring of 1939 it turned out that there were problems with the implementation of the new PZL.50 Jastrząb fighter, it was decided to temporarily implement the production of the fighter PZL P 11.G Kobuz.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Nevertheless, due to the outbreak of the war, not one of the ordered 90 aircraft of this type were delivered to the army.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The tank force consisted of two armored brigades, four independent tank battalions and some 30 companies of TKS tankettes attached to infantry divisions and cavalry brigades.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] A standard tank of the Polish Army during the invasion of 1939 was the 7TP light tank.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] It was the first tank in the world to be equipped with a diesel engine and 360° Gundlach periscope.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The 7TP was significantly better armed than its most common opponents, the German *Panzer* I and II, but only 140 tanks were produced between 1935 and the outbreak of the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Poland had also a few relatively modern imported designs, such as 50 Renault R35 tanks and 38 Vickers E tanks.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] The Polish Navy was a small fleet of destroyers, submarines and smaller support vessels.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Most Polish surface units followed Operation Peking, leaving Polish ports on 20 August and escaping by way of the North Sea to join with the British Royal Navy.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] Submarine forces participated in Operation Worek, with the goal of engaging and damaging German shipping in the Baltic Sea, but they had much less success.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p01] In addition, many merchant marine ships joined the British merchant fleet and took part in wartime convoys.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The September Campaign was devised by General Franz Halder, the chief of the general staff, and directed by General Walther von Brauchitsch the commander in chief of the German ground forces.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It called for the start of hostilities before a declaration of war, and pursued a doctrine of mass encirclement and destruction of enemy forces.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That stemmed from conservatism on the part of the German High Command, which mainly restricted the role of armour and mechanized forces to supporting the conventional infantry divisions.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Poland's terrain was well suited for mobile operations when the weather co-operated; the country had flat plains, with long frontiers totalling almost 5,600 km (3,500 mi).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Poland's long border with Germany on the west and north, facing East Prussia, extended 2,000 km (1,200 mi).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It had been lengthened by another 300 km (190 mi) on the southern side in the aftermath of the 1938 Munich Agreement.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German incorporation of Bohemia and Moravia and creation of the German puppet state of Slovakia meant that Poland's southern flank was also exposed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Hitler demanded that Poland be conquered in six weeks, but German planners thought that it would require three months.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] They intended to exploit their long border fully with the great enveloping manoeuver of *Fall Weiss*.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] All three assaults were to converge on Warsaw, and the main Polish army was to be encircled and destroyed west of the Vistula.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] *Fall Weiss* was initiated on 1 September 1939 and was the first operation of Second World War in Europe.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish determination to deploy forces directly at the German-Polish border, prompted by the Polish-British Common Defence Pact, shaped the country's defence plan, "Plan West".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Poland's most valuable natural resources, industry and population were along the western border in Eastern Upper Silesia.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish policy centred on their protection, especially since many politicians feared that if Poland retreated from the regions disputed by Germany, Britain and France would sign a separate peace treaty with Germany like the 1938 Munich Agreement and allow Germany to stay in those regions.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The fact that none of Poland's allies had specifically guaranteed Polish borders or territorial integrity was another Polish concern.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] These reasons made the Polish government disregard French advice to deploy the bulk of its forces behind natural barriers, such as the Vistula and San Rivers, despite some Polish generals supporting the idea to be a better strategy.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The West Plan allowed the Polish armies to retreat inside the country, but that was supposed to be a slow retreat behind prepared positions intended to give the armed forces time to complete its mobilization and execute a general counteroffensive with the support of the Western Allies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish General Staff had not begun elaborating the "West" defence plan until 4 March 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It was assumed that the Polish Army, fighting in the initial phase of the war alone, would have to defend the western regions of the country.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The plan of operations took into account the numerical and material superiority of the enemy and, also assumed the defensive character of Polish operations.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish intentions were defending the western regions that were judged as indispensable for waging the war, taking advantage of the propitious conditions for counterattacks by reserve units and avoiding it from being smashed before the beginning of Franco-British operations in Western Europe.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The operation plan had not been elaborated in detail and concerned only the first stage of operations.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The British and the French estimated that Poland would be able to defend itself for two to three months, and Poland estimated it could do so for at least six months.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] While Poland drafted its estimates based upon the expectation that the Western Allies would honor their treaty obligations and quickly start an offensive of their own, the French and the British expected the war to develop into trench warfare, much like World War I.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish government was not notified of the strategy and based all of its defence plans on promises of quick relief by the Western Allies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish forces were stretched thinly along the Polish-German border and lacked compact defence lines and good defence positions along disadvantageous terrain.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That strategy also left supply lines poorly protected.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] One-third of Poland's forces were massed in or near the Polish Corridor, making them vulnerable to a double envelopment from East Prussia and the west.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Another third was concentrated in the north-central part of the country, between the major cities of Łódź and Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The forward positioning of Polish forces vastly increased the difficulty of carrying out strategic maneuvres, compounded by inadequate mobility, as Polish units often lacked the ability to retreat from their defensive positions, as they were being overrun by more mobile German mechanized formations.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] As the prospect of conflict increased, the British government pressed Marshal Edward Śmigły-Rydz to evacuate the most modern elements of the Polish Navy from the Baltic Sea.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In the event of war, the Polish military leaders realized that the ships that remained in the Baltic were likely to be quickly sunk by the Germans.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Furthermore, since the Danish Straits were well within operating range of the German *Kriegsmarine* and *Luftwaffe*, there was little chance of an evacuation plan succeeding if it were implemented after hostilities began.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Four days after the signing of the Polish-British Common Defence Pact, three destroyers of the Polish Navy executed the Peking Plan and so evacuated to Great Britain.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Although the Polish military had prepared for conflict, the civilian population remained largely unprepared.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish prewar propaganda emphasized that any German invasion would be easily repelled.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That made Polish defeats during the German invasion come as a shock to the civilian population.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Lacking training for such a disaster, the civilian population panicked and retreated east, spreading chaos, lowering the troops' morale and making road transportation for Polish troops very difficult.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That led to some Polish troops being encircled or taking a stand against overwhelming odds when they thought they were actually counterattacking or would soon receive reinforcements from other victorious areas.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Following several German-staged incidents, such as the Gleiwitz incident, part of Operation Himmler, which German propaganda used as a pretext to claim that German forces were acting in self-defence, one of the first acts of war took place on 1 September 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At 04:45, the old German pre-dreadnought battleship *Schleswig-Holstein* opened fire on the Polish military transit depot and coastal fort at Westerplatte, in the Free City of Danzig, on the Baltic Sea.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] However, in many places, German units crossed the Polish border even before that time.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Around then, the Luftwaffe attacked a number of military and civilian targets, including Wieluń, the first large-scale city bombing of the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At 08:00, German troops, still without a formal declaration of war issued, attacked near the Polish village of Mokra.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Later that day, the Germans attacked Poland's western, southern and northern borders, and German aircraft began raids on Polish cities.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The main axis of attack led eastwards from Germany through the western Polish border.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Supporting attacks came from East Prussia, in the north, and a joint German-Slovak tertiary attack by units (Field Army "Bernolák") from the German-allied Slovak Republic, in the south.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] All three assaults converged on the Polish capital, Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] France and Britain declared war on Germany on 3 September, but failed to provide any meaningful support.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German-French border saw only a few minor skirmishes, and most German forces, including 85% of armoured forces, were engaged in Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Despite some Polish successes in minor border battles, the German technical, operational and numerical superiority forced the Polish armies to retreat from the borders towards Warsaw and Lwów.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Luftwaffe* gained air superiority early in the campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] By destroying communications, the *Luftwaffe* increased the pace of the advance which overran Polish airstrips and early warning sites, causing logistical problems for the Poles.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Many Polish Air Force units ran low on supplies, and 98 of their number withdrew into neutral Romania.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish initial strength of 400 was reduced to 54 by 14 September and air opposition virtually ceased, with the main Polish air bases destroyed during the first 48 hours of the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Germany attacked from three directions on land.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Günther von Kluge led 20 divisions that entered the Polish Corridor and met a second force heading to Warsaw from East Prussia.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Gerd von Rundstedt's 35 divisions attacked southern Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] By 3 September, when von Kluge in the north had reached the Vistula River, then some 10 km (6.2 mi) from the German border, and Georg von Küchler was approaching the Narew River, Walther von Reichenau's armour was already beyond the Warta river.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Two days later, his left wing was well to the rear of Łódź and his right wing at the town of Kielce.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 7 September, the defenders of Warsaw had fallen back to a 48 km (30 mi) line paralleling the Vistula River, where they rallied against German tank thrusts.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The defensive line ran between Płońsk and Pułtusk, respectively north-west and north-east of Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The right wing of the Poles had been hammered back from Ciechanów, about 40 km (25 mi) north-west of Pułtusk, and was pivoting on Płońsk.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At one stage, the Poles were driven from Pułtusk, and the Germans threatened to turn the Polish flank and thrust on to the Vistula and Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Pułtusk, however, was regained in the face of withering German fire.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Many German tanks were captured after a German attack had pierced the line, but the Polish defenders outflanked them.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] By 8 September, one of Reichenau's armoured corps, having advanced 225 km (140 mi) during the first week of the campaign, reached the outskirts of Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Light divisions on Reichenau's right were on the Vistula between Warsaw and the town of Sandomierz by 9 September, and List, in the south, was on the San River north and south of the town of Przemyśl.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At the same time, Guderian led his 3rd Army tanks across the Narew, attacking the line of the Bug River that had already encircled Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] All of the German armies made progress in fulfilling their parts of the plan.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish armies split up into uncoordinated fragments, some of which were retreating while others were launching disjointed attacks on the nearest German columns.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] During this invasion, Hitler's troops made extensive use of Pervitin, a recently discovered methamphetamine, which enabled the constant movement of the troops, who no longer felt the need to sleep for several days.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The drug would later also be used, this time officially distributed, in the invasions of France and the USSR.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish forces abandoned the regions of Pomerelia (the Polish Corridor), Greater Poland and Polish Upper Silesia in the first week.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish plan for border defence was a dismal failure.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German advance, as a whole, was not slowed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 10 September, the Polish commander-in-chief, Marshal Edward Rydz-Śmigły, ordered a general retreat to the south-east, towards the Romanian Bridgehead.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Germans were tightening their encirclement of the Polish forces west of the Vistula (in the Łódź area and, still farther west, around Poznań) and penetrating deeply into eastern Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Warsaw, which had undergone heavy aerial bombardment since the first hours of the war, was attacked on 9 September and was put under siege on 13 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Around then, advanced German forces also reached Lwów, a major city in eastern Poland, and 1,150 German aircraft bombed Warsaw on 24 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish defensive plan called for a strategy of encirclement.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It would allow the Germans to advance in between two Polish Army groups in the line between Berlin and Warsaw-Lodz, and Armia Prusy would then move in and repulse the German spearhead, trapping it.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] For that to happen, Armia Prusy needed to be fully mobilized by 3 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] However, Polish military planners failed to foresee the speed of the German advance and assumed that Armia Prusy would need to be fully mobilized by 16 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The largest battle during this campaign, the Battle of Bzura, took place near the Bzura River, west of Warsaw, and lasted from 9 to 19 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish armies *Poznań* and *Pomorze*, retreating from the border area of the Polish Corridor, attacked the flank of the advancing German 8th Army, but the counterattack failed despite initial success.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] After the defeat, Poland lost its ability to take the initiative and counterattack on a large scale.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German air power was instrumental during the battle.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The offensive of the *Luftwaffe* broke what remained of the Polish resistance in an "awesome demonstration of air power".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Luftwaffe* quickly destroyed the bridges across the Bzura River.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Then, the Polish forces were trapped out in the open and were attacked by wave after wave of *Stukas*, dropping 50 kg (110 lb) light bombs, which caused huge numbers of casualties.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish anti-aircraft batteries ran out of ammunition and retreated to the forests but were then smoked out by the Heinkel He 111 and Dornier Do 17s dropping 100 kg (220 lb) incendiaries.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Luftwaffe* left the army with the task of mopping up survivors.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Stukageschwaders* alone dropped 388 t (428 short tons) of bombs during the battle.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] By 12 September, all of Poland west of the Vistula had been conquered except for the isolated Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish government, led by President Ignacy Mościcki, and the high command, led by Marshal Edward Rydz-Śmigły, left Warsaw in the first days of the campaign and headed southeast, reaching Lublin on 6 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] From there, it moved on 9 September to Kremenez and, on 13 September to Zaleshiki, on the Romanian border.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Rydz-Śmigły ordered the Polish forces to retreat in the same direction, behind the Vistula and San Rivers, beginning the preparations for the defence of the Romanian Bridgehead area.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] From the beginning, the German government repeatedly asked Molotov whether the Soviet Union would keep to its side of the partition bargain.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Soviet forces were holding fast along their designated invasion points pending finalization of the five-month-long undeclared war with Japan in the Far East, successful end of the conflict for the Soviet Union, which occurred in the Battles of Khalkhin Gol.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 15 September 1939, Molotov and Shigenori Tōgō completed their agreement that ended the conflict, and the Nomonhan ceasefire went into effect on 16 September 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Now cleared of any "second front" threat from the Japanese, Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin ordered his forces into Poland on 17 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It was agreed that the Soviets would relinquish its interest in the territories between the new border and Warsaw in exchange for inclusion of Lithuania in the Soviet "zone of interest".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] By 17 September, the Polish defence had already been broken and the only hope was to retreat and reorganize along the Romanian Bridgehead.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Soviet diplomacy had lied that they were "protecting the Ukrainian and Belarusian minorities of eastern Poland since the Polish government had abandoned the country and the Polish state ceased to exist".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish border defence forces in the east, known as the *Korpus Ochrony Pogranicza*, had about 25 battalions.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Rydz-Śmigły ordered them to fall back and not to engage the Soviets.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That, however, did not prevent some clashes and small battles, such as the Battle of Grodno, as soldiers and locals attempted to defend the city.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Soviets executed numerous Polish officers, including prisoners of war like General Józef Olszyna-Wilczyński.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Organization of Ukrainian Nationalists rose against the Poles, and communist partisans organized local revolts, robbing and killing civilians.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Those movements were quickly disciplined by the NKVD.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Soviet invasion was one of the decisive factors that convinced the Polish government that the war in Poland was lost.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Before the Soviet attack from the east, the Polish military's plan had called for long-term defence against Germany in south-eastern Poland and to await relief from an attack by the Western Allies on Germany's western border.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] However, the Polish government refused to surrender or to negotiate peace with Germany.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Instead, it ordered all units to evacuate Poland and to reorganize in France.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Meanwhile, Polish forces tried to move towards the Romanian Bridgehead area, still actively resisting the German invasion.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] From 17 to 20 September, Polish armies *Kraków* and *Lublin* were crippled at the Battle of Tomaszów Lubelski, the second-largest battle of the campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Lwów capitulated on 22 September because of the Soviet intervention; the city had been attacked by the Germans over a week earlier, and in the middle of the siege, the German troops handed operations over to their Soviet allies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Despite a series of intensifying German attacks, Warsaw, defended by quickly-reorganized retreating units, civilian volunteers and militias, held out until 28 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Modlin Fortress north of Warsaw capitulated on 29 September, after an intense 16-day battle.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Some isolated Polish garrisons managed to hold their positions long after they had been surrounded by German forces.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The enclave of Westerplatte's tiny garrison capitulated on 7 September and the Oksywie garrison held until 19 September; the Hel Fortified Area was defended until 2 October.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Despite a Polish victory at the Battle of Szack (the Soviets later executed all the officers and NCOs they had captured), the Red Army reached the line of rivers Narew, Bug, Vistula and San by 28 September, in many cases meeting German units advancing from the other direction.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish defenders on the Hel Peninsula on the shore of the Baltic Sea held out until 2 October.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The last operational unit of the Polish Army, General Franciszek Kleeberg's *Samodzielna Grupa Operacyjna "Polesie"*, surrendered after the four-day Battle of Kock near Lublin on 6 October, marking the end of the September Campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish Campaign was the first action by Hitler in his attempt to create *Lebensraum* (living space) for Germans.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Nazi propaganda was one of the factors behind the German brutality directed at civilians that had worked relentlessly to convince the Germans into believing that Jews and Slavs were *Untermenschen* (subhumans).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] From the first day of invasion, the German air force (the *Luftwaffe*) attacked civilian targets and columns of refugees along the roads to terrorize the Polish people, disrupt communications and target Polish morale.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Luftwaffe* killed 6,000 to 7,000 Polish civilians during the bombing of Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German invasion saw atrocities committed against Polish men, women and children.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish women and girls were raped en masse by the German invaders and then executed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In addition, large numbers of Polish women were routinely captured to force them into prostitution in German military brothels.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Nazi raids in many Polish cities captured young women and girls, who were then forced to work in the brothels frequented by German officers and soldiers.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Girls as young as 15 years old, who were classified as "fit for agricultural work in Germany", were sexually exploited by German soldiers at their destination.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Altogether, the civilian losses of Polish population amounted to about 100,000 or between 150,000 and 200,000, the large majority of which were due to German war operations and terror.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In Warsaw alone, 15,000 to 25,000 civilians lost their lives.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The deaths also included 12,136 Polish citizens of Polish and Jewish background killed in 615 known executions perpetrated by the German military, police and security forces before the close of the operations within the post-war borders of Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In the German-occupied territories, a mass ethnic cleansing campaign called Operation Tannenberg was started in the course of the hostilities by the Wehrmacht and the Einsatzgruppen.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Roughly 1,250 German civilians were also killed during the invasion.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The invasion of Poland marked the beginning of the Holocaust ("holocaust by bullets"), not only in its strict sense of the genocide of Jews, but also in its broader meaning of mass killings of various ethnic, political or social groups.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] American journalist John Gunther wrote in December 1939 that "the German campaign was a masterpiece.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Nothing quite like it has been seen in military history".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The country was divided between Germany and the Soviet Union.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Slovakia gained back those territories taken by Poland in autumn 1938.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Lithuania received the city of Vilnius and its environs on 28 October 1939 from the Soviet Union.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 8 and 13 September 1939, the German military district in the area of Posen, commanded by general Alfred von Vollard-Bockelberg, and West Prussia, commanded by general Walter Heitz, were established in conquered Greater Poland and Pomerelia, respectively.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Based on laws of 21 May 1935 and 1 June 1938, the German military delegated civil administrative powers to Chiefs of Civil Administration (*CdZ*).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Hitler appointed Arthur Greiser to become the CdZ of the Posen military district, and Danzig's Gauleiter Albert Forster to become the CdZ of the West Prussian military district.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 3 October 1939, the military districts centered on and named "Lodz" and "Krakau" were set up under command of major generals Gerd von Rundstedt and Wilhelm List, and Hitler appointed Hans Frank and Arthur Seyß-Inquart as civil heads, respectively.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Thus the entirety of occupied Poland was divided into four military districts (West Prussia, Posen, Lodz, and Krakau).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Frank was at the same time appointed "supreme chief administrator" for all occupied territories.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 28 September, another secret German–Soviet protocol modified the arrangements of August: all of Lithuania was shifted to the Soviet sphere of influence; in exchange, the dividing line in Poland was moved in Germany's favour, eastwards towards the Bug River.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 8 October, Germany formally annexed the western parts of Poland with Greiser and Forster as *Reichsstatthalter*, while the south-central parts were administered as the General Government led by Frank.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Even though water barriers separated most of the spheres of interest, the Soviet and German troops met on numerous occasions.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The most remarkable event of this kind occurred at Brest-Litovsk on 22 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German 19th *Panzer* Corps—commanded by General Heinz Guderian—had occupied the city, which lay within the Soviet sphere of interest.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] When the Soviet 29th Tank Brigade (commanded by Semyon Krivoshein) approached, the commanders agreed that the German troops would withdraw and the Soviet troops would enter the city, saluting each other.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At Brest-Litovsk, Soviet and German commanders held a joint victory parade before German forces withdrew westward behind a new demarcation line.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The German troops left the area, and the Red Army troops entered Lwów on 22 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Molotov–Ribbentrop pact and the invasion of Poland marked the beginning of a period during which the government of the Soviet Union increasingly tried to convince itself that the actions of Germany were reasonable, and were not developments to be worried about, despite evidence to the contrary.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] About 65,000 Polish troops were killed in the fighting (and roughly 3,000 prisoners of war were executed), with 420,000 others being captured by the Germans and 240,000 more by the Soviets (for a total of 660,000 prisoners).
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Up to 120,000 Polish troops escaped to neutral Romania (through the Romanian Bridgehead and Hungary), and another 20,000 to Latvia and Lithuania, with the majority eventually making their way to France or Britain.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Most of the Polish Navy succeeded in evacuating to Britain as well.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] German personnel losses were less than their enemies (c.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] None of the parties to the conflict—Germany, the Western Allies or the Soviet Union—expected that the German invasion of Poland would lead to a war that would surpass World War I in its scale and cost.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It would be months before Hitler would see the futility of his peace negotiation attempts with the United Kingdom and France, but the culmination of combined European and Pacific conflicts would result in what was truly a "world war".
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The invasion of Poland led Britain and France to declare war on Germany on 3 September.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] However, they did little to affect the outcome of the September Campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] No declaration of war was issued by Britain and France against the Soviet Union.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] This lack of direct help led many Poles to believe that they had been betrayed by their Western allies.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] British Foreign Secretary Lord Halifax said they were only obligated to declare war on Germany due to the first clause of the Anglo-Polish Agreement in 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] On 23 May 1939, Hitler explained to his officers that the object of the aggression was not Danzig, but the need to obtain German *Lebensraum* and details of this concept would be later formulated in the infamous *Generalplan Ost*.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Since October 1939, the Polish army that could escape imprisonment from the Soviets or Nazis were mainly heading for British and French territories.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] These places were considered safe, because of the pre-war alliance between Great-Britain, France and Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Not only did the government escape, but also the national gold supply was evacuated via Romania and brought to the West, notably London and Ottawa.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The approximately 75 tonnes (83 short tons) of gold was considered sufficient to field an army for the duration of the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The American journalist and filmmaker Julien Bryan came to besieged Warsaw on 7 September 1939 in the time of German bombardment.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] He photographed the beginning of the war by using one roll of colour film (Kodachrome) and much black-and-white film.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] He made one film about German crimes against civilians during the invasion.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In colour, he photographed Polish soldiers, fleeing civilians, bombed houses, and a German bomber He 111 destroyed by the Polish Army in Warsaw.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] His photographs and film *Siege* are stored in the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Polish cavalry units did not engage German tanks with lances and swords.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] At the Battle of Tuchola Forest on 1 September 1939 the 18th Pomeranian Uhlan Regiment had been tasked to cover the retreat of Polish infantry.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In the evening the Pomeranian Uhlans encountered contingents of the advancing German 20th Infantry Division of Heinz Guderian's XIX Army Corps.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Commander Kazimierz Mastalerz ordered an attack, forcing the 20th infantry to withdraw and disperse.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The engagement proved to be successful as the German advance had been delayed.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] However, upon redeployment, the 18th Pomeranians came under sudden and intense machine gun fire of German armored reconnaissance vehicles.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Despite their quick retreat, nearly a third of the Uhlans were killed or wounded.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] A group of German and Italian war correspondents, who visited the battlefield noticed the dead cavalry men and horses among the armored vehicles.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Italian reporter Indro Montanelli promptly published an article in the *Corriere della Sera*, on the brave and heroic Polish cavalry men, who charged German tanks with sabres and lances.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] In 1939, 10% of the Polish army was made up of cavalry units.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish Air Force was not destroyed on the ground in the first days of the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Though numerically inferior, it had been redeployed from major air bases to small camouflaged airfields shortly before the war.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Only some trainers and auxiliary aircraft were destroyed on the ground.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The Polish Air Force, despite being significantly outnumbered and with its fighters outmatched by more advanced German fighters, remained active until the second week of the campaign, inflicting significant damage on the *Luftwaffe*.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] The *Luftwaffe* lost 285 aircraft to all operational causes, with 279 more damaged, and the Poles lost 333 aircraft.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Another question concerns whether Poland inflicted any significant losses on the German forces and whether it surrendered too quickly.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] While exact estimates vary, Poland cost the Germans about 45,000 casualties and 11,000 damaged or destroyed military vehicles, including 993 tanks and armored cars, 565 to 697 airplanes and 370 artillery pieces.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] As for duration, the September Campaign lasted about a week and a half less than the Battle of France in 1940 even though the Anglo-French forces were much closer to parity with the Germans in numerical strength and equipment and were supported by the Maginot line.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Furthermore, the Polish Army was preparing the Romanian Bridgehead, which would have prolonged Polish defence, but the plan was invalidated by the Soviet invasion of Poland on 17 September 1939.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Poland also never officially surrendered to the Germans.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Under German occupation, there was continued resistance by forces such as the *Armia Krajowa*, Henryk Dobrzański's guerrillas, and the Leśni ("forest partisans").
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] It is often assumed that *Blitzkrieg* is the strategy that Germany first used in Poland.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] That idea has been repudiated by some authors.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] Zaloga and Madej, in *The Polish Campaign 1939*, also address the subject of mythical interpretations of *Blitzkrieg* and the importance of other arms in the campaign.
[src:abbeville/1939-defensive-war-p02] They argue that Western accounts of the September campaign have stressed the shock value of the *panzers* and *Stuka* attacks have "tended to underestimate the punishing effect of German artillery on Polish units.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The **Polish 1st Armoured Division** (Polish *1 Dywizja Pancerna, Pierwsza Dywizja Pancerna*) was an armoured division of the Polish Armed Forces in the West during World War II.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] Created in February 1942 at Duns in Scotland, it was commanded by Major General Stanisław Maczek and at its peak numbered approximately 18,000 soldiers.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The division served in the final phases of the Battle of Normandy in August 1944 during Operation Totalize and the Battle of Chambois and then continued to fight throughout the campaign in Northern Europe, mainly as part of the First Canadian Army.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] After the fall of Poland and then France in 1940, many of the remaining Poles that had fought in both campaigns retreated with the British Army to the United Kingdom.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] Stationed in Scotland, the Polish 1st Armoured Division was formed as part of the Polish I Corps under Wladyslaw Sikorski, which guarded approximately 200 kilometres of British coast in 1940-1941.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The commander of the Division, General Stanislaw Maczek, was Poland’s premier mechanized commander, and many of his subordinate officers from the unit he commanded in 1939, the 10th Mechanized Brigade, had made their way to Britain with him.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] They were organized on the British Armoured Division model, equipped with British uniforms, weapons and tanks.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] They were initially equipped and trained on Crusader tanks but in late 1943 and early 1944 these were replaced with Sherman and Cromwell tanks.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] They then participated in war games together with the 4th Canadian (Armoured) Division.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] By the end of July 1944, the 1st Armoured had been transferred to Normandy, its final elements arriving on 1 August on Arromanches, Grayes and Courseulles sur mer where a memorial has been erected.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The unit was attached to the First Canadian Army as part of the 21st Army Group.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] This may have been done to help in communication, as the vast majority of Poles did not speak English when they arrived in the United Kingdom from 1940 onwards.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The Division entered combat on 8 August during Operation Totalize.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] It twice suffered serious casualties as a result of "friendly fire" from Allied aircraft, but achieved a victory against the Wehrmacht in the battles for Mont Ormel, and the town of Chambois.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] This series of offensive and defensive operations came to be known as the Battle of Falaise, in which a large number of German Army and SS divisions were trapped in the Falaise Pocket and subsequently destroyed.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] Surrounded and running out of ammunition, they withstood incessant attacks from multiple fleeing panzer divisions for 48 hours until they were relieved.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The division's total losses from August 7 when it entered combat until the end of the battle of Falaise on August 22 were 446 killed, 1,501 wounded, and 150 missing, or 2,097 soldiers in total during about two weeks of fighting.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] After the Allied armies broke out from Normandy, the Polish 1st Armoured Division pursued the Germans along the coast of the English Channel.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] It liberated, among others, the towns of Saint-Omer, Ypres, Oostnieuwkerke, Roeselare, Tielt, Ruislede, and Ghent.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] During Operation Pheasant, a successful outflanking manoeuvre planned and performed by General Maczek allowed the liberation of the city of Breda without any civilian casualties (29 October 1944).
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The Division spent the winter of 1944-1945 on the south bank of the river Rhine, guarding a sector around Moerdijk, Netherlands.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] In early 1945, it was transferred to the province of Overijssel and started to push with the Allies along the Dutch-German border, liberating the eastern parts of the provinces of Drenthe and Groningen including the towns of Emmen, Coevorden and Stadskanaal.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] In April 1945, the 1st Armoured entered Germany in the area of Emsland.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] On 6 May, the Division seized the Kriegsmarine naval base in Wilhelmshaven, where General Maczek accepted the capitulation of the fortress, naval base, East Frisian Fleet and more than 10 infantry divisions.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] The majority of its soldiers opted not to return to Poland, which fell under Soviet occupation, preferring instead to remain in exile.
[src:abbeville/1st-armoured-division-poland] Many artefacts and memorabilia belonging to Maczek and the 1st Polish Armoured Division are on display in the Polish Institute and Sikorski Museum in London.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in France on 21 and 22 April 2007 to elect the successor to Jacques Chirac as president of France (and *ex officio* Co-Prince of Andorra) for a five-year term.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] As no candidate received a majority of the vote, a second round was held on 5 and 6 May 2007 between the two leading candidates, Nicolas Sarkozy and Ségolène Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy was elected with 53% of the vote.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy and Royal both represented a generational change.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Both main candidates were born after World War II, along with the first to have seen adulthood under the Fifth Republic, and the first not to have been in politics under Charles de Gaulle.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] In addition, Royal was the first woman in France's history to reach the second round in a presidential election.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy ran for re-election in 2012, but was defeated by Royal's lifelong partner at the time, François Hollande.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Since the death of Lionel Jospin in 2026, it is the earliest French presidential election in which either of the second round candidates is still alive.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] For the first time in a presidential election, electronic voting was introduced in some areas, having been authorised in 2004.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] They were introduced in only 82 of 36,000 voting districts, and were criticised by a number of people, both on the left and on the right.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] A petition against them has also been made (see Wikinews:Electronic voting disputed in France).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Using the three colours of the national flag (blue, white, and red) on electoral advertisements or partisan documentation was prohibited by electoral regulations.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Ségolène Royal contended that the book *Ensemble* ("together") published by Nicolas Sarkozy, whose cover is blue, white and red, was effectively an electoral partisan documentation and should have been covered by this prohibition.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] The requirements for being successfully nominated as a candidate are defined by the organic law of 6 November 1962.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] All candidates had to be of French nationality and at least 23 years old (the same requirement as for the candidates to the National Assembly).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Candidates must obtain signatures from 500 elected officials (mayors, members of Parliament, elected representatives) supporting their candidacy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] These signatures from elected officials (informally known in French as *parrainages*, but legally known as "presentations") must be from at least 30 departments or overseas territories, and no more than 10 percent can be from any individual department.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] A presentation from an elected official does not imply the official supports the policies of the candidate, but rather that this official considers the candidate to be a serious candidate.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Candidates must also submit a statement with details of their personal assets.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] The Constitutional Council published the official candidate list on 20 March 2007.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] The candidates were listed in a randomised order.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] This order was used for the official campaign: thus, posters for Olivier Besancenot were to always be displayed on the No.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] 1 board, those for Marie-George Buffet on the No.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] 2 board, etc., regardless of where in France the boards were located.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] There were 12 candidates for the 2007 election.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Four candidates consistently registered over 10% in the opinion polls and were regarded as having a reasonable chance of reaching the second round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] These were the eight other candidates who obtained the required 500 signatures from elected officials to endorse their candidacy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Approximately 200 French intellectuals expressed support for Ségolène Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Régis Debray called to vote first for a far-left candidate, then Royal in the second round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] On the other hand, the so-called *Nouveaux Philosophes* were split on their support.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] André Glucksmann called to vote Sarkozy, while Bernard-Henri Lévy voted for Ségolène Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Max Gallo, who had supported the left-wing Republican Jean-Pierre Chevènement in 2002, joined Sarkozy five years later.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Pascal Bruckner and Alain Finkielkraut have also proved close to Sarkozy, although they did not declare support for him, but Sarkozy did support Finkielkraut after controversial statements made in *Haaretz* newspaper following the 2005 civil unrest.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] According to the journalist Jacques Julliard, the support of some French intellectuals for the 2003 invasion of Iraq is the root of their rallying to Sarkozy, following the creation of the review titled *Le Meilleur des mondes* (Brave New World).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Pascal Bruckner, historian Stéphane Courtois, Thérèse Delpech, André Glucksmann, Romain Goupil, Pierre-André Taguieff, Olivier Rollin, and Pierre Rigoulot are frequent contributors to this review.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Tennis player Yannick Noah called to vote for Royal, while Sarkozy obtained the support of singers Johnny Hallyday, Mireille Mathieu and Faudel, of rapper Doc Gyneco, and former politician and current actor Bernard Tapie.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] He also had the support of actors Jean Reno and Christian Clavier, both residing in Neuilly-sur-Seine where Sarkozy was the mayor between 1983 and 2002 and of Gérard Depardieu.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] But also of industrialist Martin Bouygues, whose children attended the same school as Sarkozy's offspring.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Comedian Dieudonné and author Alain Soral supported Jean-Marie Le Pen.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Actress Juliette Binoche supported José Bové.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Prominent political commentator Alain Duhamel was suspended in 2006 after a video was published on DailyMotion, where he stated his personal intentions of voting for François Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Abroad, Silvio Berlusconi, the former prime minister of Italy, gave his support to Sarkozy immediately following the first round, while Romano Prodi, the then Italian premier and leader of the centre-left Union coalition, called for an alliance between Bayrou and Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Spanish Prime Minister José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has shown his support for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] European commissioner and Vice-President Margot Wallström was criticised after she informally suggested support for Royal on her blog, celebrating the fact that a woman got into the second round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Wallström is a social-democrat, like Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] José Manuel Barroso, the head of the European Commission, has privately discussed the idea of forming a "strategic partnership" with Mr.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Many U.S. pundits and western economists expressed support for Nicolas Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Steve Forbes devoted several columns in the influential financial publication *FORBES Magazine*.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] The London-based magazine *The Economist* also expressed support for Sarkozy's economic platform .
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] In 2011, according to the son of the Libyan leader Saif Al-Islam Gaddafi, Sarkozy was provided with financial support from Libya during the presidential election.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] In 2012, Mediapart published material revealing Gaddafi's financial support to Nicolas Sarkozy for the election.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] In March 2018 Sarkozy was charged for corruption.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] French law prohibits publishing the results of opinion polls related to the election during the day of the election and the preceding day, so as to prevent undue influencing of the vote.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] No estimate can be given before Sunday 20:00, when the last voting office closes and official counts begin to be released.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] However, media from neighbouring countries, which are not bound by these regulations, have long broadcast estimates (Télévision Suisse Romande in particular).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] In 2007, the issue took a particular importance because of the generalisation of blogs and Internet pages.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Journalist Jean-Marc Morandini stirred turmoil when he announced his intention of publishing results on his blog as soon as 18:00.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p01] Another problem was that the results from the voting offices in the Americas (consulates and French overseas possessions) were counted on Saturday night, and some began circulating rumours as to these results.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The first round saw a very high turnout of 83.8% – 36.7 million of the 44.5 million electorate voted from a population of 64.1 million (not including French people living abroad).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The results of that round saw Sarkozy and Royal qualify for the second round with Sarkozy getting 31% and Royal 26%.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] François Bayrou came third (19%) and Jean-Marie Le Pen fourth (10%), unlike in 2002 when Le Pen got a surprising 16.9% and qualified for the second round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Immediately after the first round's results were made official, four defeated left-wing candidates – José Bové, Marie-George Buffet, Arlette Laguiller and Dominique Voynet – urged their supporters to vote for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] This was the first time since 1981 that Laguiller had endorsed the Socialist Party's candidate.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Olivier Besancenot called his supporters to vote against Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Frédéric Nihous and Gérard Schivardi never officially supported either Royal or Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Philippe de Villiers called for a vote for Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Le Pen told his voters to "abstain massively" in the second round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] On 25 April, Bayrou declared he would not support either candidate in the runoff, and announced he would form a new political party called the Democratic Movement.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] He criticised both major candidates, and offered to debate them.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Royal agreed to hold a televised debate, while Sarkozy offered to have a private discussion but not a televised debate.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] By around 18:15 local time on 6 May, Belgian and Swiss news sources such as *Le Soir*, RTBF, *La Libre Belgique* and *La Tribune de Genève* had announced Nicolas Sarkozy as the winner of the second round, citing preliminary exit poll data.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The final CSA estimate showed him winning with 53% of the votes cast.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Royal conceded defeat to Sarkozy that evening.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Nationwide, Nicolas Sarkozy obtained 31% and Ségolène Royal 26% – while in 2002, Jacques Chirac had obtained 20%, and Lionel Jospin 16.18%.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The right-of-centre François Bayrou obtained 18.6% this time, nearly tripling his 2002 result (6.8%).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] National Front (FN) candidate, Jean-Marie Le Pen, made only 10.4%, compared to his stunning 16.9% finish in 2002.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Along with the April–May shift to the far right made by Sarkozy, this has led many commentators to allege that traditional voters of the FN had been tempted by Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Overall, the left-wing reached 36% of the votes, against 19% for the "centre", 33% for the right wing and 11% for the far right.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Other candidates received a much lower share of the vote than they had in 2002, with Olivier Besancenot (Revolutionary Communist League, LCR) failing to achieve the 5% necessary to have his political campaign reimbursed by the state.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Besancenot received 4.1%, compared to 4.3% in 2002.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] With an overall record turnout of 83.8%, a level not achieved since the 1965 presidential election when turnout was 84.8%, the vast majority of the electorate decided not to stay home.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Most of them decided against protest votes, and chose the *vote utile* (tactical voting, literally "useful vote"), that is, a vote for one of the purported leaders of the electoral race (Nicolas Sarkozy, Ségolène Royal and/or François Bayrou).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The "Anyone But Sarkozy" push benefited both Bayrou and Royal, while the tactical voting, on the right or on the left, explains the low score of the other candidates, in contrast with the last presidential election's first round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] The electoral campaign saw a polarisation of the political scene, encapsulated by the "Anyone But Sarkozy" slogan on the left.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] But it also saw a reconfiguration of the political chessboard, with various left-wing figures and voters deciding to support Sarkozy against Royal, who saw opposition inside her own party.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Bernard Tapie, a former Socialist, Max Gallo, who had supported left-wing Republican Jean-Pierre Chevènement in 2002, Eric Besson, etc., passed on Sarkozy's side.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] On the other hand, some right-wing voters, upset by Sarkozy's attitude on law and order, immigration, and even genetics (his recent declarations on paedophilia, homosexuality and suicides as genetically induced, denounced by the geneticist Axel Kahn), decided to vote for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] Former socialist minister Claude Allègre stated such an alliance was "entirely conceivable", while Royal herself strongly criticised Rocard's comments.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p02] François Hollande, the national secretary of the Socialist Party and Ségolène Royal's partner, excluded any alliance with the centre-right, along with others left-wing leaders, such as Laurent Fabius or Dominique Voynet.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In urban areas, most lower and middle-income neighbourhoods and cities voted largely for Ségolène Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In the tenth arrondissement of Paris, Royal obtained 42% against 25% for Sarkozy, and 20.35% for Bayrou; in the 11th arrondissement, Royal obtained more than 40.8% to 25.8% for Sarkozy and 20.9% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In the 18th arrondissement, Royal obtained 41.1% against 23.4% for Sarkozy; in the 19th arrondissement, Royal obtained more than 39%, against almost 28% for Sarkozy; and in the 20th arrondissement, Royal obtained 42.4% against 23.2% for Sarkozy, and 18.3% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Working-class Paris suburbs (called *les banlieues*) also massively voted for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] This was more or less expected, in particular with the high level of voter registration by suburban youths, who had been strongly opposed to Sarkozy since the 2005 riots during which he had made controversial remarks.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Meanwhile, a large number of university students had participated in the protests against the CPE, proposed by Sarkozy's UMP party, in the spring of 2006; they also strongly backed Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] She consequently came first in Nanterre, with almost 36% against 23% for Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] She reached 41.6% in Saint-Denis, against 19.6% for Sarkozy and 15.5% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In Évry, she also passed the 40% line, while Sarkozy received only 23.6%.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In Créteil, she won a closer race, gaining 35% to Sarkozy's 30% and 18% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In the department of Seine-Saint-Denis, home to many people of immigrant origin, Royal obtained 34.2% to 26.8% for Sarkozy and 16.7% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In contrast, wealthy arrondissements of Paris voted for Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The mostly wealthy Paris suburbs of the Hauts-de-Seine department, home of Neuilly-sur-Seine where Sarkozy is mayor, voted 38.3% for him, against 26% for Royal and 21.3% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy also won in the Essonne department (more than 31% against 27% for Royal), in the Seine-et-Marne (33.5% to almost 24% for Royal) as well as in the Yvelines (37.7% against 23% for Royal and 22% for Bayrou).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Marseille, the second-largest city of France, went Sarkozy's way overall as he won 34.25% of the vote to 27.1% for Royal and only 14.1% for Bayrou (putting a close third ahead of Le Pen, who obtained 13.4%).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] However, in working-class neighbourhoods of the north of Marseille, such as Savine (15th arrondissement) and the Busserine (14th arrondissement), Royal received overwhelming support, receiving 60% of the vote in Busserine.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] France's third-largest city, Lyon, also was won by Sarkozy, who received 34.5% of the vote to 27.3% for Royal and 22% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] He triumphed as well in the wealthy city of Aix-en-Provence with 36.8%, against 25.4% for Royal and 19.8% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In Nice, a conservative stronghold, Sarkozy obtained more than 41% against 20.4% for Royal and less than 15% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy also narrowly beat Royal in the industrial port of Le Havre (29% against 26.8%), as well as in Avignon, Nîmes, Metz, Nancy, and Strasbourg (these last three cities belonging to the Alsace-Lorraine region).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] A map of France's departments shows the candidate of the Socialist Party, Ségolène Royal, came first in the South-West and the Massif Central, which were traditional bases of the Radical-Socialist Party during the Third Republic.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] She also topped the poll in Brittany, except in the department of Morbihan, but a fifth of electors in Brittany voted for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Nièvre and Seine-Saint-Denis were other departments where she came first, as well as the overseas departments of Martinique and Réunion and the overseas territory of Saint Pierre and Miquelon.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy came first everywhere else, except for Pyrénées-Atlantiques, where Bayrou topped the poll in the department of his birth.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The left regressed, compared 2002, in the Nord-Pas-de-Calais region, which has traditionally favored Socialist and Communist candidates.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The Nord department, hit hard during the 1980s by an industrial crisis, gave a plurality to Sarkozy (29.3%), while Royal won 24.8% (and won the city of Lille) and Bayrou received 15.6%.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Marie-George Buffet barely received 5% in the constituency of the Communist deputy Alain Bocquet.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The Haute-Garonne, traditional Radical-Socialist territory, voted (including its capital, Toulouse), for Ségolène Royal, giving her 33%, against less than 27% for Sarkozy and slightly more than 19% for Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The Corrèze, where Jacques Chirac began his political career as the deputy of Ussel, also voted slightly in favour of Royal, as did the Creuse, one of the least-populated departments of France.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The Vaucluse department gave 32.8% of its votes to Sarkozy, 20.9% to Royal, 16.8% to Le Pen and 15.5% to Bayrou.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The Vendée voted 29.7% for Sarkozy, 21.7% for Royal, 20.8% for Bayrou, and 11.3% for Philippe de Villiers, deputy of the department.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Le Pen's highest departmental tallies occurred in Aisne (17.3%) and Haute-Marne (17%).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The overseas department of Martinique has been strongly opposed to Sarkozy; Aimé Césaire, mayor of Fort-de-France and leader of the *Négritude* movement, refused to see him during his visit there in December 2005 (due to the UMP vote of the 2005 law on colonialism).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In the first round, it heavily supported Royal (48.5%, against 33.8% for Sarkozy and only 8.6% for Bayrou; the next highest total was received by Besancenot, with 2.5%).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Réunion also strongly supported Royal (46.2%, to 25% for Sarkozy and 13% for Bayrou).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Meanwhile, Sarkozy won in New Caledonia (with 49.7% of the vote) and in Guadeloupe (with 42.6%, against 38.3% for Royal), as well as in French Guiana and the overseas territories of French Polynesia and Wallis and Futuna.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 30% of men voted for Sarkozy, 24% of them for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 29% of 18- to 24-year-olds voted Royal, against 26% for Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy also made a higher score for 35- to 44-year-olds and 60- to 69-year-olds, but a lesser score in the 45- to 59-year-old category.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 36% of farmers voted Sarkozy against 8% for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Workers voted at similar levels for both Sarkozy and Royal (21% for each), while public servants voted at 34% for Royal (18% for Sarkozy).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 19% of unemployed people voted for Sarkozy, 32% of them for Royal.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Students also voted in majority for Royal (32% against 21%), while pensioned elders voted at 41% for Sarkozy (23% for Royal).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The second round of the 2007 French presidential election started in Saint Pierre and Miquelon on Saturday 5 May 2007 at 8 am local time (2007-05-05 10:00 UTC) and ended in the large cities of Metropolitan France on Sunday, 6 May 2007 at 8 pm local time (2007-05-06 18:00 UTC).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Turnout in the second round of the election was 84.0%, higher than in the first round.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Nicolas Sarkozy got 53.06% of the votes and Ségolène Royal got 46.94%.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The left-right division was reinforced, according to many observers, by the election of Nicolas Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 91% of the electors self-identifying as members of the centre-left voted for Royal, and 92% of those who self-identified as centre-right voted for Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The center thus appears to have been polarized.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The vast majority of the dissident left also voted for Royal, while the extreme right strongly supported Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Although Jacques Chirac was successful among young electors in 1995, mostly owing to his discourse on the "social rupture" (*fracture sociale*), Sarkozy's electorate was more traditionally right-wing and focused on older people.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The only age group that gave him a majority was the over-50, who accounted for 52% of his voters, compared to only 37% of Royal's.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy obtained only 40% among those 18–24 years old, while Chirac had obtained 55% in the same category in 1995.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] In social categories, Sarkozy won majorities among pensioned and inactive elders (58%), business leaders, shopkeepers and craftworkers (82% ), categories which are traditionally conservative.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Sarkozy lost votes, compared to Chirac, among workers (59% for Royal) and employees (57% for Royal).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] The general electoral geography did not significantly change from the first Chirac election.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] However, Sarkozy received a lesser score in Corrèze, Chirac's home department, and bettered Chirac's score in the North-East, where Le Pen had obtained some of his better scores in 2002.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Overall, the increase in votes for Sarkozy between the two rounds occurred mostly in departments where the National Front's presence is strong.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Spoilt votes represented 4.2% of the electors (as much as in 2002 and 1995).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Abstention was exceptionally low, as well as protest votes.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Blank vote (going to vote, but deliberately cancelling one's ballot, by any means possible – tearing it in two, writing Tintin on it, or anything absurd as such) is not included in official counts – i.e. it is considered a spoilt vote, counted as equivalent to abstention.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] A very small party, the *Parti Blanc* (White Party, for "white vote", i.e. blank vote) called for the official count of white votes by the state (as in None of the above systems).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] It organised a march in Paris on Wednesday 18 March 2007 in which only thirty people participated.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Thousands of youths took to the streets Sunday night following the final presidential election results.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] While many simply expressed their discontent at the election of Nicolas Sarkozy, others chose to engage in violent action.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Riots erupted in several urban centers including the capital Paris where some of the most intense clashes were reported in the Place de la Bastille.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] A gathering of opponents to Sarkozy there quickly ended in confrontations between the youth and the riot control forces, who tear gassed the whole place.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 732 cars were torched according to estimates of the DGPN (direction of the police) and government buildings and property came under attack.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Police clashed with protesters who were described by French media as members of the ultra-left and of the autonome movement or youth from the suburbs.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] During the fighting dozens of officers were injured and 592 alleged rioters were arrested.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 70 people were arrested in the North department and 79 in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Some clashes continued on the night of Monday to Tuesday, with 365 torched cars and 160 alleged rioters detained by the police.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Ten people were in court already by Monday.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Two of them were given firm prison sentences of six and three months respectively, and two others to 120 hours of TIG (General Interest Labour, an alternative sentence to prison).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Another one has been given a two-month firm prison sentence and two others TIG hours.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] Some of the people judged in Lyon have denied any involvement in the riots (two of them received 120 hours of TIG and a 200 euros fine).
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] 300 to 400 people demonstrated on the Boulevard Saint-Michel on Wednesday 9 May, in opposition to a demonstration of white supremacists.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] By 9 pm that night 118 of them had been arrested.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] A 31-year-old engineer took legal action following his release from custody claiming he had been a victim of police brutality.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] He claimed that he had not taken part to the demonstrations, but had been arrested nonetheless.
[src:abbeville/2007-french-presidential-election-p03] On 20 March 2018, Sarkozy was arrested by the French Police because of the suspect having received 50 million euros for his presidential campaign from Muammar Gaddafi.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] The **2011 Tour de Picardie** was the 65th edition of the Tour de Picardie cycling stage race.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] It started on 13 May in Abbeville and ended on 15 May in Peronne and consisted of three stages.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] The race was won by Team Vacansoleil-DCM rider Romain Feillu, who claimed the leader's yellow and blue jersey after a strong finish on the 3rd stage.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] Feillu' winning margin over runner-up Kenny De Haes of Omega Pharma-Lotto was 8 seconds, and Katusha's Filippo Pozzato completed the podium, 8 seconds down on Feillu.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] In the race's other classifications, Omega-Pharma Lotto rider Kenny de Haes won the points classification's green jersey.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] Bretagne-Schuller rider Johan Lethe King of the Mountains classification, with Saur-Sojasun finishing at the head of the teams classification.
[src:abbeville/2011-tour-de-picardie] The winner of the 2010 Tour de Picardie, Ben Swift, was not looking to defend last year's victory because of his racing at the 2010 Tour of California, while other pre-race favourites like 3 stage winner of Tour Méditerranéen winner, Romain Feillu, as well as Kenny Dehaeswho was 5th at 2008.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The incumbent Nicolas Sarkozy was running for a second five-year term for which he was eligible for under the Constitution of France.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The first round ended with the selection of François Hollande and Nicolas Sarkozy as second round participants, as neither of them received a majority of votes cast in the first round.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Hollande won the runoff with 51.64% of the vote to Sarkozy's 48.36%.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Hollande was the former partner of Ségolène Royal, whom Sarkozy defeated five years earlier in 2007.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] It was the second time in French history and the first time since the 1981 election that a President seeking reelection was denied a second term, and the only time the incumbent seeking reelection did not obtain the most votes in the first round.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The presidential elections were followed by legislative elections in June.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] This is the last French presidential election in which the winning candidate won by a single-digit margin.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] This is also the case for French residents in foreign countries west of metropolitan France.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Some of these communities are remote; Amerindians in French Guiana, who are French citizens, "sometimes live more than three hours away by canoe from their ballot box", particularly in the large remote commune of Maripasoula.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The electoral campaign papers sent to these voters, however, reportedly indicated 22 April as the day of the election, instead of 21 April.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The number of signatures per candidate is not released, but five hundred signatories for each candidate are chosen randomly and their names are published.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The 2011 French Socialist Party presidential primary was the first open primary (*primaires citoyennes*), jointly held by the French Socialist Party and Radical Party of the Left for selecting their candidate for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Voters had to donate at least one Euro and sign a pledge to the values of the Left to be eligible.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The filing deadline for primary nomination papers was fixed on 13 July 2011 and six candidates competed in the first round of the vote.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] On election day, 9 October 2011, no candidate won at least 50% of the vote therefore the two candidates with the most votes contested a runoff election on 16 October 2011: François Hollande won the primary, defeating Martine Aubry.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The idea for holding an open primary to choose the Socialist Party candidate was originally suggested in 2008 by the left-leaning think tank Terra Nova.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Europe Écologie–The Greens (EELV) held a primary to choose its candidate.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The vote was open to all members of the party and of the Independent Ecological Movement.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The first round was held on 29 June 2011.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Eva Joly, a member of EELV and a former examining magistrate, obtained 49.75% of the vote, ahead of independent candidate and environmental campaigner Nicolas Hulot (40.22%).
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The other two candidates, Henri Stoll and Stéphane Lhomme, obtained 5.02% and 4.44% respectively.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The second round was held on 12 July, with Eva Joly obtaining 13,223 votes (58.16%) to Hulot's 9,399.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The official campaign began on 20 March, but in the wake of the shooting at the Ozar Hatorah day school in Toulouse the two leading candidates, Hollande and Sarkozy, suspended their campaigns.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The following is a brief overview of the campaign adapted from information in *Le Monde*.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] François Hollande, the candidate of the Socialist Party and the Radical Party of the Left, topped the opinion polls throughout the campaign.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He emphasised his promise to be a "normal" president, in contrast to Nicolas Sarkozy's sometimes controversial presidential style.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He aimed to resorb France's national debt by 2017, notably by cancelling tax cuts for the wealthy and tax exemptions introduced by President Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Income tax would be raised to 75% for incomes beyond one million euros; the retirement age would be brought back to 60 (with a full pension) for persons who have worked 42 years; 60 000 jobs cut by Nicolas Sarkozy in public education would be recreated.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Homosexual couples would have the right to marry and adopt.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Residents without European Union passports would be given the right to vote in local elections after five years of legal residency.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] On housing, he has promised to regulate rises in rent; to use punitive measures to compel towns and cities to apply the 2000 Law on Solidarity and Urban Renewal, which mandates the providing of social housing; and to provide public lands for the building of social housing.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Hollande won the election, finishing first on the first balloting of ten candidates in April with 28.63% of the vote, and again finishing first on the runoff ballot between himself and Sarkozy with 51.64% against Sarkozy's 48.36%.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Nicolas Sarkozy, the incumbent president and candidate of the Union for a Popular Movement, was aiming for a second and last term in office.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He was consistently second in opinion polls throughout the campaign, behind François Hollande.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] His reforms during his first term included a reform of universities, and of the retirement age; a reform enabling citizens to query the constitutionality of laws; and a reduction in the number of public sector employees.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He argued that his reforms had helped steer France through a period of economic crisis.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy's campaign pledges for his potential second term are described by *Le Monde* as "anchored on the right".
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He has also promised more frequent referendums, for citizens to be consulted on major issues.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy admitted during the campaign that he did not visit Fukushima while in Japan after the previous year's earthquake and tsunami, despite having previously said he had done so.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Marine Le Pen is the candidate of the National Front, succeeding her father Jean-Marie Le Pen, who was a candidate in five presidential elections.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Aiming to reach the second round, as her father had done in 2002, she also attempted to provide a different image of the party, avoiding the controversial statements previously made by her father.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She has advocated "national preference" for French citizens (over foreign residents) for access to jobs and social services, and a form of protectionism, as well as withdrawing from the euro and the European Union.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She has advocated reducing legal immigration by 95%, abolishing the right to family reunification, and reinstating the death penalty, abolished in 1981 by then president François Mitterrand.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She held the third place in opinion polls for much of the campaign, occasionally rising into first and second place in 2011 or dipping to fourth behind Jean-Luc Mélenchon, but remained consistently behind Hollande and Sarkozy by 2012.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She finished the 2012 balloting with 17.90% of the vote tally, placing her third in the final results.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Jean-Luc Mélenchon is the candidate of the Left Front, which includes in particular the French Communist Party and the Left Party.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] (He is a member of the latter.) He has been described as the surprise or revelation of the campaign, with his level of support in opinion polls rising from 5% in October 2011 to around 15% (and sometimes up to 17%) by the end of the campaign.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He finished in the first round of balloting with 11.10% of the national electorate, placing him fourth in the field of 10 candidates.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He inaugurated the practice of giant open-air meetings, which the two leading candidates then adopted in turn.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] A former French teacher, he was noted for his eloquent style and oratory, but also for his argumentative relationship with journalists, and occasional insults; he notably described Marine Le Pen as "half-demented".
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] There would be an "ecological planification" towards a green, sustainable economy, backed by a "green rule" (*règle verte*) to be inscribed in the Constitution.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] On tax, he has proposed a progressive taxation, with higher taxes on the wealthy and a 100% tax rate beyond an income of €360,000 (thereby creating a maximum wage); expatriate French nationals established in a country with a lower tax rate than in France would pay the difference in tax in France.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Businesses creating jobs, paying higher wages and/or providing training would receive tax cuts.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Healthcare costs would be fully reimbursed by the state, and the right to die would be recognised.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The right to abortion would be secured through inclusion in the Constitution.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Naturalisation of foreign residents would be facilitated, and foreign residents would have the right to vote in local elections.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] A constitutional convention would be assembled, with an aim in particular to increase the prerogatives of Parliament and diminish the powers of the President; all elections would be based on proportional representation, with gender parity.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] François Bayrou was the candidate of the Democratic Movement, which he founded in 2007.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He is one of only two candidates to stand in both the 2007 and 2012 elections (the other being Nicolas Sarkozy); he obtained 18.57% of the vote in 2007, finishing third.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] In the 2012 election he received 9.13% of the vote in the first round of balloting, finishing fifth.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He stands for an independent centre in politics, which he has sought to distinguish clearly both from the left and the right.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Describing France as being "in a critical state", he has focused on reducing the country's national debt, through a public spending freeze, cuts to tax exemptions, and a raise in taxes (Value added tax and taxes on the wealthy).
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] On education, he has proposed that half the time in primary school should be dedicated to the mastering of reading and writing.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Eva Joly was the candidate of Europe Écologie–The Greens.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Before entering politics for this election, she was a known public figure, as the examining magistrate in criminal corruption cases involving powerful companies or individuals – notably the Elf Aquitaine oil company, the Crédit Lyonnais bank or businessman and politician Bernard Tapie.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] (See: Elf affair (fr).) She is also the first foreign-born person to stand for the French presidency; born in Norway, she is a naturalized French citizen.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She focused her campaign not only on the environment but also on social issues, describing herself as the representative of the "reasonable" or "realistic" left, and on denouncing discrimination against ethnic and religious minorities.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Homosexual couples would be given the right to marry and adopt, and foreign residents would have the right to vote in all elections.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She suggested that the "ecological transformation of the economy" would create 600 000 jobs over the next five years.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] An agreement signed between her party and the Socialist Party contained a clause on the closing of nuclear reactors; in the final stages of the campaign, when François Hollande announced it would not be upheld, she expressed the hope she could still convince him.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She also drew attention by accusing Nicolas Sarkozy of having obtained illicit funding for his previous campaign; critics accused her of ignoring the presumption of innocence, and Sarkozy himself replied that he "despised" her accusations.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Known for her bright red glasses, which she symbolically switched for bright green ones, she was described by the press as struggling with her campaign, barely reaching 3% in opinion polls.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Nicolas Dupont-Aignan, described as an "anti-euro souverainist", is the candidate of Arise the Republic, a party he founded in 2008.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He has advocated leaving the euro on grounds of economic well-being, and the European Union "in its current form", which he describes as "already dead" and leading to "economic ruin and social regression".
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He has called for an "intelligent protectionism", with tariffs on imports that result from "human slavery"; and tax cuts for businesses that reinvest their profits in France.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Philippe Poutou, a worker at a Ford factory in Blanquefort, is the candidate of the New Anticapitalist Party, succeeding Olivier Besancenot.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] For much of the campaign, he remained little known to the general public; he was described as lacking Besancenot's popularity, charisma and ease with words.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] In particular, his unconventional behaviour drew attention during the television programme *Des paroles et des actes* (fr), along with his unusual campaign clips – such as one based on the film *The Artist*.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Like Nathalie Arthaud, his message was that improvements in workers' rights would come through workers' struggles and demands rather than through the ballot box.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Nathalie Arthaud, a teacher of economics and management in a secondary school, is the candidate of Workers' Struggle.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She succeeds famous perennial candidate Arlette Laguiller, who represented the party in six consecutive presidential elections, from 1974 to 2007.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] A Trotskyist, she has described herself as the "only communist candidate" in the election.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] She has stated that she does not aim to be elected, describing elections as "inessential", and considering that workers will obtain new rights only through their struggles rather than through the ballot box.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Jacques Cheminade is the candidate of his Solidarity and Progress movement, the French branch of the LaRouche movement.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Described as a "conspiracy theorist" by the press, he drew some attention with his proposals for an expanded space programme, and stagnated slightly above 0% in the opinion polls.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Since the first round there had been a drive to woo far-right voters with Sarkozy making immigration a major issue of his campaign and Hollande focusing on the euro-zone crisis and the state of the economy.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy's move to the right in embracing National Front themes such as stricter immigration has drawn criticism from prominent figures from his own party such as former Prime Ministers Dominique de Villepin, Jean-Pierre Raffarin, Alain Juppé and Senators Chantal Jouanno and Jean-René Lecerf.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] There was more criticism of the German-led austerity measures by Hollande, while he also responded to Sarkozy's words at a rally in Toulouse saying that "without borders there is no nation, there is no Republic, there is no civilisation.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] We are not superior to others but we are different." In turn Hollande told a bigger rally in Paris that "I want victory, but not at any price, not at the price of caricature and lies.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] I want to win over the men and women who are angry, a hundred times yes, but compromise myself?
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] A thousand times no." Sarkozy reiterated threats to withdraw from the Schengen Agreement if there was no tightening of border controls.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] He also said that there would be a presumption of self-defense when police are involved in the killing of suspects and criticised the EU's lack of mention of Europe's Christian roots in its constitution.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Many of the issues were similar to that of the National Front, from which Sarkozy's UMP gained votes between the 2002 and 2007 election.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Le Pen stated she would submit a blank ballot in the run-off, calling on her supporters to make their own choices.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Bayrou announced on 3 May that he would vote for Hollande.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] German Chancellor Angela Merkel also said she saw nothing "normal" in Hollande, despite his attempts to portray himself as such; instead she supported Sarkozy's campaign.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] In the last government bond sale before the election, the previously rising yields fell slightly, while the amount sold was marginally lower than expected.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The campaign has led to a "certain degree of gridlock in EU's corridors of power".
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] It's unclear who will be the head of the Euro Group, who will join the Executive Board of the European Central Bank (ECB) and who will lead the European Stability Mechanism (ESM).
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] In the days before the election, editorials in the main newspapers expressed opinions about the two candidates.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Of the candidates who went out in the first round, Bayrou, Joly and Cheminade all explicitly declared their support for Hollande in the second round, while Mélenchon and Poutou implicitly endorsed a vote for Hollande by urging their supporters to vote against Sarkozy.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Dupont-Aignan backed Sarkozy, while Le Pen and Arthaud declined to support either candidate.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] There was one televised debate between Hollande and Sarkozy, although Sarkozy said he would prefer three, an idea Hollande rejected.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Hollande accused Sarkozy of dividing the French and failing to lower unemployment.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Hollande promised to be a president for social justice, economic recovery and national unity.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Sarkozy was said to have told Hollande that his lack of experience in national government made him unfit for the task of leading the world's fifth-largest economy in a crisis.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] French law sets a blackout of the release of exit polls until the last polling station is closed at 20:00, with fines of up to €75,000.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] The hashtag #RadioLondres was used as it recalls the coded messages from World War II sent by *Radio Londres*.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] EU-based media outlets not subject to the French blackout law reported early exit poll results before closure of the polls, in both rounds of the election.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p01] Olivier Cimelière reported that some people saw a risk of manipulating future elections.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] François Hollande received 51.64% of the votes, while Nicolas Sarkozy secured 48.36% of the votes in the second round.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] Sarkozy became the first one-term president since Valéry Giscard d'Estaing lost to François Mitterrand in 1981.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] Sarkozy called for UMP to "stay together.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] We must win the battle of the legislatives" and said that "in this new era, I will remain one of you, but my place will no longer be the same.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] He then travelled to Paris, where supporters of the Socialist Party gathered outside the headquarters.
[src:abbeville/2012-french-presidential-election-p02] He also said that "Europe is watching us.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The **2012 Tour de France** was the 99th edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] It started in the Belgian city of Liège on 30 June and finished on the Champs-Élysées in Paris on 22 July.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The Tour consisted of 21 stages, including an opening prologue, and covered a total distance of 3,496.9 km (2,173 mi).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] As well as the prologue, the first two stages took place in Belgium, and one stage finished in Switzerland.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Bradley Wiggins (Team Sky) won the overall general classification, and became the first British rider to win the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins's teammate Chris Froome placed second, and Vincenzo Nibali (Liquigas–Cannondale) was third.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The general classification leader's yellow jersey was worn for the first week by Fabian Cancellara (RadioShack–Nissan), who won the prologue.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The points classification was won by Nibali's teammate Peter Sagan, who won three stages.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] André Greipel of Lotto–Belisol and Team Sky rider Mark Cavendish also won three stages.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Team Europcar's Thomas Voeckler, winner of two mountain stages, won the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] BMC Racing Team's Tejay van Garderen, in fifth place overall, won the young rider classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The team classification was won by RadioShack–Nissan, and Chris Anker Sørensen (Saxo Bank–Tinkoff Bank) was given the award for the most combative rider.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The 2012 edition of the Tour de France featured 22 teams.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The race was the 18th of the 29 events in the UCI World Tour, and all of its eighteen UCI ProTeams were entitled, and obliged, to enter the race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] On 6 April 2012, the organiser of the Tour, Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), announced the four second-tier UCI Professional Continental teams given wildcard invitations, of which three were French-based (Cofidis, Team Europcar and Saur–Sojasun) and one was Dutch (Argos–Shimano).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The presentation of the teams – where the members of each team's roster are introduced in front of the media and local dignitaries – took place outside the Prince-Bishops' Palace in Liège, Belgium, on 28 June, two days before the opening stage held in the city.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Each squad was allowed a maximum of nine riders, resulting in a start list total of 198 riders.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Of these, 35 were riding the Tour de France for the first time.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The riders came from 31 countries; France, Spain, Netherlands, Italy, Belgium, Germany and Australia all had 12 or more riders in the race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Riders from six countries won stages during the race; British riders won the largest number of stages, with seven.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The average age of riders in the race was 30.17 years, ranging from the 22-year-old Thibaut Pinot (FDJ–BigMat) to the 40-year-old Jens Voigt (RadioShack–Nissan).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The Saur–Sojasun cyclists had the youngest average age while RadioShack–Nissan cyclists had the oldest.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] According to many observers before the race the favourite for the general classification was Bradley Wiggins.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] His closest rivals were thought to be Cadel Evans (BMC Racing Team) and Vincenzo Nibali (Liquigas–Cannondale).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Alberto Contador, the winner of both the 2007 Tour and 2009 Tour, was serving a doping suspension and did not race in the 2012 Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Andy Schleck, who finished second in the 2010 Tour (later promoted to the winner after Contador's result was annulled in February 2012) and 2011 Tour, was not able to recover from an injury suffered in the Critérium du Dauphiné.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Prior to the 2012 Tour, Wiggins's highest finishes in a Grand Tour were third in the 2011 Vuelta a España and fourth in the 2009 Tour (later promoted to third after Lance Armstrong's result was annulled in October 2012).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins had shown his form in the lead-up to the Tour by winning the general classifications in three stage races in the 2012 season: the Paris–Nice, the Tour de Romandie and the Dauphiné.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] As a time trialist, Wiggins was thought to be the rider most suited to the race's course.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The 2011 Tour winner Evans came back from an illness earlier in the season to win the two-day Critérium International and place third at the Dauphiné.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The 2010 Vuelta a España winner Nibali had shown his form in the lead-up to the Tour by winning the Tirreno–Adriatico stage race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The sprinters considered favourites for the points classification and wins in bunch sprint finishes were Mark Cavendish (Team Sky), André Greipel (Lotto–Belisol), Matthew Goss (Orica–GreenEDGE), Peter Sagan (Liquigas–Cannondale) and Marcel Kittel (Argos–Shimano).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Cavendish, the world road race champion and defending points classification winner, did not have the full support of Team Sky as he did in the 2011 Tour with the HTC–Highroad team; Team Sky's focus was on Wiggins' general classification ambitions.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] He had won the four-stage race Ster ZLM Toer 13 days before the start of the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Greipel, who had the full backing of his team, had shown his form in the season with thirteen victories up to the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Goss was second to Cavendish at the world championships and was the new sprint leader of his team, although he had only one win in the year up to the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Sagan was equal in wins with Greipel with thirteen, of which five came in the Tour of California and four in the Tour de Suisse.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Kittel won two stages in both the Tour of Oman and Ster ZLM Toer.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] On 29 October 2010, the ASO announced that Liège would host the 2012 edition's opening stages (known as the *Grand Départ*).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Further details of the first three stages held in Belgium were released at an event at the city's Prince-Bishops' Palace on 18 November.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Liège, which had also hosted the 2004 *Grand Départ*, became the first city outside France to host the *Grand Départ* twice.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The entire route of the race was accidentally published on the ASO website on 10 October 2011, eight days before the official presentation at the Palais des Congrès in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] At the event, the race director, Christian Prudhomme, said, "It's a Tour designed to widen the possibilities".
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The route was noted as being innovative when compared to recent years, with fewer high altitude stage finishes, and more of a focus on medium mountain stages and individual time trials.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Due to a clash with the start of the Olympics at the end of July, the Tour began a week earlier than usual.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] After the opening prologue in Liège, stage one left the city with the finish in Seraing.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The second stage took place between Visé to Tournai.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The race then moved into north-west France, with the third stage ending in the coastal city of Boulogne-sur-Mer, before the fourth ended in Rouen, and the fifth in Saint-Quentin.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage six took the race east, with the seventh ending in the Vosges Mountains.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage eight then entered the Jura Mountains, with the finish in Porrentruy, Switzerland.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A return to France saw the next stage take place between Arc-et-Senans to Besançon.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The next stages, ten and eleven, went into the Alps, and stages twelve and thirteen took the Tour down to the Mediterranean coast at Cap d'Agde.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage fourteen moved the race into the east of Pyrenees, before a transitional stage taking it to the western side of the mountains for the next two stages.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage eighteen was held between Blagnac to Brive-la-Gaillarde in the south of the country, before a long transfer took the race back to the north-east for two further stages, with the finish on the Champs-Élysées in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] There were 21 stages in the race, covering a total distance of 3,496.9 km (2,173 mi), 133.1 km (82.7 mi) shorter than the 2011 Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The longest mass-start stage was the twelfth at 226 km (140 mi), and stage 21 was the shortest at 120 km (75 mi).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The race featured twice the time trialling distance of the previous Tour, a total of 101.1 km (63 mi), with the prologue, stage nine and stage nineteen.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Of the remaining stages, nine were officially classified as flat, four as medium mountain and five as high mountain.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] There were three summit finishes: stage 7, to La Planche des Belles Filles; stage 11, to La Toussuire-Les Sybelles; and stage 17, to Peyragudes.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The Col du Grand Colombier, in the Alps, was included for the first time, and was among six *hors catégorie* (English: beyond category) rated climbs in the race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was the 2,115 m (6,939 ft)-high Col du Tourmalet mountain pass on stage sixteen.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] There were nine new stage start or finish locations.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The rest days were after stage nine, in Mâcon, and fifteen, in Pau.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The opening 6.4 km (4 mi) prologue stage in Liège was won by RadioShack–Nissan's Fabian Cancellara.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Bradley Wiggins and Sylvain Chavanel (Omega Pharma–Quick-Step) placed second and third respectively, both seven seconds in arrears, with Wiggins fractionally faster.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Cancellara claimed the yellow jersey as leader of the general classification and the green jersey as leader of the points classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In stage one, a large group of riders reached the final climb, the Côte de Seraing.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Cancellara attacked 1.5 km (0.9 mi) from the finish, followed by Peter Sagan and Edvald Boasson Hagen (Team Sky), before Sagan won the three-man sprint finish at the summit.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Michael Mørkøv of Saxo Bank–Tinkoff Bank took the first polka dot jersey as leader of the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The next stage was won by Mark Cavendish from a bunch sprint finish in Tournai, Belgium, with Sagan taking the green jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage three, the first in France, saw Sagan win again, crossing the finish line with a comfortable margin on the short steep climb in Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The fourth stage ended with a bunch sprint which was won by André Greipel.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A crash with 3 km (1.9 mi) remaining took Cavendish out of contention for the stage win.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Another bunch finish occurred on the next stage, with Greipel victorious again.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The sixth stage was won by Sagan in another bunch sprint.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In stage seven, the first at altitude, the last of the day's breakaway riders were caught with 1.5 km (0.9 mi) remaining, on the final climb to La Planche des Belles Filles.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A select group of five – Wiggins and his compatriot and teammate Chris Froome, Cadel Evans, Vincenzo Nibali and Rein Taaramäe (Cofidis) – then pulled clear in the final kilometre.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Evans attacked before Froome countered and went on to win the stage and take the polka dot jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Cancellara lost almost two minutes on the day and surrendered the yellow jersey to Wiggins, who became the fifth British rider to wear the jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The eighth stage saw breakaway rider Thibaut Pinot attack a reduced break on the final climb, the Col de la Croix, and solo to the finish in Porrentruy, Switzerland, taking the victory by margin of 26 seconds.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Breakaway rider Fredrik Kessiakoff (Astana) took the polka dot jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Stage nine's 41.5 km (25.8 mi) individual time trial was won by Wiggins, with Froome 35 seconds down in second and Cancellara a further 22 seconds behind in third.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The next day was the first rest day of the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The tenth stage was the first classified as mountainous.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The Col du Grand Colombier broke apart a 25-rider breakaway, leaving a small group to contest the finish at Bellegarde-sur-Valserine; Thomas Voeckler (Team Europcar) claimed the stage win and the polka dot jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Another mountain stage followed the next day, which again saw a large breakaway.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The break crossed the two *hors catégorie* climbs – the Col de la Madeleine and the Col de la Croix de Fer – before being caught by the chasing group, which contained the overall contenders.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A number of attacks followed, until Team Europcar's Pierre Rolland escaped with 10 km (6.2 mi) to go and took the win at the Les Sybelles ski resort.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The group of overall contenders followed 55 seconds later.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Evans was not in the leading contenders group and, due to the time lost, he dropped from second to fourth overall, over three minutes in arrears.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Kessiakoff took back the lead of the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In stage twelve, a large breakaway formed 20 km (12.4 mi) in, before later reducing to five riders across the Col du Granier.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] They stayed together until the finish, where, with a kilometre remaining, David Millar (Garmin–Sharp) escaped to take victory, closely followed by Jean-Christophe Péraud (Ag2r–La Mondiale).
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The next stage finished with a bunch sprint won by Greipel, with Sagan second.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the first stage in the Pyrenees, the fourteenth stage overall, a large breakaway escaped 50 km (31.1 mi) in, and at one point amassed a lead of fifteen minutes.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Of the five remaining riders from the final climb of Mur de Péguère, Luis León Sánchez of Rabobank attacked on an ascent with 11.5 km (7.1 mi) remaining and soloed to the finish in Foix.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] As the peloton (the main group) passed the Mur de Péguère, a large number of riders suffered tyre punctures; it was later discovered that the race course had been sabotaged with carpet tacks.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Evans waited over a minute to get a replacement wheel, then had a further two punctures on the descent.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] As an act of sportsmanship Wiggins then forced the peloton to wait for Evans to return to the group.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The next stage ran through the foothills of the Pyrenees.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A five-rider breakaway made it to the finish in Pau, where with 6 km (3.7 mi) to go, Christian Vande Velde (Garmin–Sharp) and Pierrick Fédrigo (FDJ–BigMat) escaped with Fédrigo winning the sprint finish between the two cyclists.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The following day was the Tour's second rest day.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the sixteenth stage, the race entered the high mountains with the queen stage crossing two *hors catégorie* climbs – the Col d'Aubisque and the Col du Tourmalet – followed by the first-category climbs of the Col d'Aspin and the Col de Peyresourde, completing the so-called "Circle of Death".
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A 38-rider breakaway crossed the Aubisque, before fracturing on the Tourmalet.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Voeckler attacked on the Peyresourde and took the stage win with a margin of one minute and forty seconds.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Voeckler's stage victory and maximum points over all summits put him in the lead of the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins, Froome and Nibali came in seven minutes after Voeckler, while Evans lost almost five minutes to the trio, falling from fourth to seventh in the general classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the final stage in the Pyrenees, the seventeenth, after a number of attacks on the leading group containing the overall contenders, Alejandro Valverde moved clear over the *hors categorie* Port de Balès.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] He held his lead to the summit finish at the Peyragudes ski resort.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the group behind, Wiggins and Froome attacked their rivals to finish nineteen seconds later.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Nibali came in seventh, a further eighteen seconds down.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the following stage, six riders from a breakaway were caught on the finishing straight in Brive-la-Gaillarde by the head of the chasing peloton, with Cavendish taking the victory ahead of Matthew Goss and Sagan respectively.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins secured the general classification in the penultimate stage's 53.5 km (33.2 mi) individual time trial.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Froome placed second, one minute and sixteen seconds behind, with Sánchez a further 34 seconds behind in third.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In the final stage, Cavendish won his fourth consecutive Champs-Élysées stage, to record his third stage win of the race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins finished the race to become the first British rider to win the Tour de France.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins finished 3 min 21 s clear of compatriot and teammate Froome.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Nibali placed third at 6 min 19 s behind Wiggins.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Sagan won the points classification with a total of 421, 141 ahead of Greipel in second.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Voeckler won the mountains classification with 135 points, 12 ahead of second-placed Kessiakoff.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The best young rider was BMC Racing Team rider Tejay van Garderen, who was followed by Pinot and Steven Kruijswijk (Rabobank) in second and third respectively.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] RadioShack–Nissan finished as the winners of the team classification, over 5 min 46 s ahead of second-placed Team Sky.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Of the 198 starters, 153 reached the finish of the last stage in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] During the race's first rest day, the team hotel of the Cofidis squad, in Bourg-en-Bresse, was searched by French police and gendarmerie.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] One of the team's riders in the Tour, Rémy Di Gregorio, was arrested in relation to an ongoing anti-doping case, and was immediately suspended by the French team, although the case had been open since 2011, when Di Gregorio was a member of the Astana team.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The second rest day was marked by a positive drugs test by Fränk Schleck, the third-placed rider from the 2011 Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Schleck was withdrawn from the race by his team after traces of xipamide, a banned sulfonamide diuretic drug, were found in the A-sample of his urine; the presence of xipamide was later confirmed by the B-sample.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Subsequently, in January 2013, he was given a one-year ban by the Luxembourg Anti-Doping Agency.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In July 2014, Denis Menchov was retroactively disqualified from the race by cycling's governing body, *Union Cycliste Internationale*, for "abnormalities in his biological passport".
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] There were four main individual classifications contested in the 2012 Tour de France, as well as a team competition.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The most important was the general classification, which was calculated by adding each rider's finishing times on each stage.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] There were no time bonuses given at the end of stages for this edition of the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] If a crash had happened within the final 3 km (1.9 mi) of a stage, not including time trials and summit finishes, the riders involved would have received the same time as the group they were in when the crash occurred.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The rider with the lowest cumulative time was the winner of the general classification and was considered the overall winner of the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The rider leading the classification wore a yellow jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The second classification was the points classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Riders received points for finishing in the top fifteen positions in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints during the stage.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The points available for each stage finish were determined by the stage's type.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The flat stage finishes awarded a maximum of 45 points, the medium mountain stages awarded a maximum of 30 points, and the high mountain stages, time trials and intermediate sprints awarded a maximum of 20 points.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The leader was identified by a green jersey.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The third classification was the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Most stages of the race included one or more categorised climbs, in which points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit first.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second- or first-category and *hors catégorie*, with the more difficult climbs rated lower.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Fourth-category awarded 1 rider with 1 point; third-category awarded 2 riders, the first with 2 points; second-category awarded 4 riders, the first with 5 points; and first-category awarded 6 riders, the first with 10 points; and *hors catégorie* awarded ten riders, the first with 25 points.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Double points were awarded on the summit finishes on stages 1, 11 and 20.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The leader wore a white jersey with red polka dots.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The final individual classification was the young rider classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] This was calculated the same way as the general classification, but the classification was restricted to riders who were born on or after 1 January 1987.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The final classification was a team classification.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] This was calculated using the finishing times of the best three riders per team on each stage; the leading team was the team with the lowest cumulative time.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The number of stage victories and placings per team determined the outcome of a tie.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that lead this classification were identified with yellow number bibs on the back of their jerseys and, for first the time in the Tour's history, wore yellow helmets.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] In addition, there was a combativity award given after each stage to the rider considered, by a jury, to have "made the greatest effort and who has demonstrated the best qualities of sportsmanship".
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] No combativity awards were given for the prologue, the time trials and the final stage.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The winner wore a red number bib the following stage.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] At the conclusion of the Tour, Chris Anker Sørensen (Saxo Bank–Tinkoff Bank) won the overall super-combativity award, again, decided by a jury.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] A total of €2,414,246 was awarded in cash prizes in the race.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The overall winner of the general classification received €450,000, with the second and third placed riders getting €200,000 and €100,000 respectively.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] All finishers of the race were awarded money.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The holders of the classifications benefited on each stage they led; the final winners of the points and mountains classifications were given €25,000, while the best young rider and most combative rider got €20,000.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The team classification winners were given €50,000.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Pierre Rolland won the Henri Desgrange and Thomas Voeckler won the Jacques Goddet.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Riders from the ProTeams competing individually, as well as for their teams and nations, for points that contributed towards the World Tour rankings.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Points were awarded to the top twenty finishers in the general classification and to the top five finishers in each stage.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Wiggins moved into the lead of the individual ranking, with Joaquim Rodríguez dropping to second.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] The points accrued by Chris Froome moved him from 52nd to 6th.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Team Sky retained their lead in the team ranking, ahead of second-place Liquigas–Cannondale.
[src:abbeville/2012-tour-de-france] Spain remained as the leaders of the nation ranking, with Italy second.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The **2015 Tour de France** was the 102nd edition of the Tour de France, one of cycling's Grand Tours.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The 3,360.3 km (2,088 mi)-long race consisted of 21 stages, starting on 4 July in Utrecht, the Netherlands, and concluding on 26 July with the Champs-Élysées stage in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A total of 198 riders from 22 teams entered the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The overall general classification was won by Chris Froome of Team Sky, with the second and third places taken by Movistar Team riders Nairo Quintana and Alejandro Valverde, respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] BMC Racing Team's Rohan Dennis won the first stage to take the general classification leader's yellow jersey.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Trek Factory Racing rider Fabian Cancellara claimed it on the second, only to lose it after crashing out on the following stage.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] This put Froome in the lead, after the Tour's first uphill finish.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He lost the position to Etixx–Quick-Step's Tony Martin at the end of the fourth stage, but Martin's withdrawal from the race after a crash at the end of the sixth stage put Froome back into the lead.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He extended this lead during the stages in the Pyrenees and defended it successfully against attacks from Quintana during the final stages that took place in the Alps.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome became the first British rider to win the Tour twice, after his 2013 victory.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Peter Sagan of Tinkoff–Saxo won the points classification.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome also won the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The best young rider was Quintana, with his team, Movistar, the winners of the team classification.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Romain Bardet of AG2R La Mondiale was given the award for the most combative rider.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] André Greipel (Lotto–Soudal) won the most stages, with four.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Twenty-two teams participated in the 2015 edition of the Tour de France.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The race was the 18th of the 28 events in the UCI World Tour, and all of its seventeen UCI WorldTeams were automatically invited, and obliged, to attend the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On 14 January 2015, the organiser of the Tour, Amaury Sport Organisation (ASO), announced the five second-tier UCI Professional Continental teams given wildcard invitations, one of which, MTN–Qhubeka, was to become the first African-registered trade team to participate in the race's history.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The team presentation – where the members of each team's roster are introduced in front of the media and local dignitaries – took place at Lepelenburg Park in Utrecht, the Netherlands, on 2 July, two days before the opening stage held in the city.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Each team arrived in small boats along the Oudegracht canal.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Each squad was allowed a maximum of nine riders, therefore the start list contained a total of 198 riders.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Of these, 45 were riding the Tour de France for the first time.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The riders came from 32 countries; France, the Netherlands, Italy, Spain, Belgium, Australia, Germany, Great Britain and Switzerland all had 10 or more riders in the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Eritrean riders Daniel Teklehaimanot and Merhawi Kudus, both of MTN–Qhubeka, became the first black Africans to compete in the Tour de France.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Riders from nine countries won stages during the race; German riders won the largest number of stages, with six.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The average age of riders in the race was 29.67 years, ranging from the 21-year-old Kudus to 41-year-old Matteo Tosatto (Tinkoff–Saxo).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Of the total average ages, Cofidis was the youngest team and Trek Factory Racing the oldest.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] In the lead up to the Tour, the main contenders for the general classification, known in the media as the 'big four', were Chris Froome (Team Sky), Alberto Contador (Tinkoff–Saxo), Nairo Quintana (Movistar Team) and Vincenzo Nibali (Astana).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] All had won at least one Grand Tour, amassing a total of twenty Grand Tour podiums.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Former Tour de France winners Froome (2013) and Contador (2007 and 2009) returned to the race having crashed out of the 2014 edition.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The other riders considered contenders were Tejay van Garderen (BMC Racing Team), Thibaut Pinot (FDJ), Joaquim Rodríguez (Team Katusha), followed by AG2R La Mondiale's Jean-Christophe Péraud and Romain Bardet.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome had shown his form during the season with overall victories at the Vuelta a Andalucía and the Critérium du Dauphiné, a race considered to be the warm-up for the Tour.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Contador had earlier in the season won the Giro d'Italia and was aiming to become the first rider since Marco Pantani in 1998 to achieve the Giro-Tour double.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He was also aiming to hold all three Grand Tour titles simultaneously, having won the 2014 Vuelta a España.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Thirteen days before the start of the Tour, Contador won the Route du Sud, defeating Quintana by seventeen seconds.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Quintana placed second in the 2013 Tour, winning the mountains and young rider classifications.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He was absent in 2014 as he concentrated on the Giro d'Italia, which he won.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] His major victory of the 2015 season was the Tirreno–Adriatico.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The defending champion Nibali was considered a contender, although his best result of the season was tenth in the Tour de Romandie, and placed thirteenth at the Dauphiné.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The sprinters considered favourites for the points classification and wins on the flat or hilly bunch sprint finishes were Alexander Kristoff (Team Katusha), Mark Cavendish (Etixx–Quick-Step), André Greipel (Lotto–Soudal), Peter Sagan (Tinkoff–Saxo) and John Degenkolb (Team Giant–Alpecin).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Kristoff and Cavendish both showed their form during the season coming into the Tour, with eighteen and twelve wins, respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Greipel was also a contender, spearheaded by his sprint train, much like Cavendish.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Three-time consecutive winner of the points classification Sagan was expected to have a hard time repeating as winner due to the changes in the classification's point structure and also due to the fact he had to ride in support of Contador.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Degenkolb, who won the one-day classic races Milan–San Remo and Paris–Roubaix in the season, would take the lead of the Team Giant–Alpecin team due to the absence of the 2014 Tour's four-stage winner Marcel Kittel, who was not selected due to lack of fitness.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On 8 November 2013, the ASO announced Utrecht would host the 2015 edition's opening stages (known as the *Grand Départ*).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] It was the sixth time the Tour had started in the Netherlands, a record for a country outside France.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The previous five were: 1954, in Amsterdam; 1973, in Scheveningen; 1978, in Leiden; 1996, in 's-Hertogenbosch; and 2010, in Rotterdam.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Utrecht paid the ASO a reported €4m to host the *Grand Départ*.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The full route of the Tour was unveiled on 22 October 2014 at the Palais des Congrès in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] At the event, the race director Christian Prudhomme described it as "*atypique*" (English: "atypical"), adding "If you do not climb, you will not win the Tour in 2015." The most noticeable differences were the lack of time trial kilometres and the mountainous terrain.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] After the first stage in Utrecht, the second stage left the city to finish in the region of Zeeland in the south of the Netherlands.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The third began in Antwerp, Belgium, and concluded at the Mur de Huy, a steep climb known for its inclusion in the one-day classic race La Flèche Wallonne.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage four started in Seraing, before ending in Cambrai, France; it featured seven cobbled sectors with a combined distance of 13 km (8.1 mi).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stages five to nine crossed northern France westwards, beginning in the region of Nord-Pas-de-Calais and ending in Brittany.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A long transfer took the race to the south of the country for next three stages through the Pyrenees, which include the Tour's most climbed mountain, the Col du Tourmalet, on stage eleven.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stages 13 to 16 formed a continuous four-stage journey that navigated eastwards to the Alps; four stages took place in and around the mountain range.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A second long transfer took the Tour back to the north-east to finish with the Champs-Élysées stage in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] There were 21 stages in the race, covering a total distance of 3,360.3 km (2,088 mi), 298.7 km (185.6 mi) shorter than the 2014 Tour.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The longest mass-start stage was the fourth at 223.5 km (139 mi), and stage 21 was the shortest at 110.5 km (69 mi).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The opening individual time trial was 13.8 km (8.6 mi) – although it was too long to be classified a prologue – and the team time trial on stage 9 was 28 km (17.4 mi).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Of the remaining stages, seven were officially classified as flat, five as medium mountain and seven as high mountain.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stages 3 and 8, although classified as flat, finished at the 204 m (669 ft)-high Mur de Huy and 293 m (961 ft)-high Mûr-de-Bretagne respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] There were six summit finishes: stage 10, to La Pierre Saint-Martin; stage 11, to Cauterets; stage 12, to Plateau de Beille; stage 17, to Pra-Loup; stage 19, to La Toussuire to Les Sybelles; and stage 20, to Alpe d'Huez.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On 25 June, it was announced that due to a landslide, the route of stage twenty would be changed, bypassing the Col du Galibier and instead climbing the Col de la Croix de Fer.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The stage distance, however, remained intact.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The highest point of elevation in the race was the 2,250 m (7,380 ft)-high Col d'Allos mountain pass on stage seventeen.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] There were seven *hors catégorie* (English: beyond category) rated climbs in the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The Tour included six new start or finish locations.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The rest days were after stage 9, in Pau, and after 16, in Gap.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The race's opening individual time trial stage in Utrecht was won by Rohan Dennis of BMC Racing Team by a margin of five seconds over Etixx–Quick-Step's Tony Martin, with Trek Factory Racing's Fabian Cancellara a further second down.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Dennis set the record for the fastest average speed in a time trial at the Tour, with 55.446 km/h (34.5 mph).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] His win put him in the race leader's yellow jersey.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On stage two, crosswinds along the coastal route to the finish in Zeeland caused the peloton (the main group) to split into echelons, resulting in time gaps between riders.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The stage ended in a bunch sprint, won by André Greipel, putting him in the green jersey as the leader of the points classification.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Dennis was in a group that finished one minute twenty-eight seconds in arrears.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Cancellara finished third placed in the stage and took the race lead, profiting from a time bonus missed by Martin, who came in ninth.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The general classification favourites that gained time from being in the leading group of twenty-six were Chris Froome, Alberto Contador and Tejay van Garderen; the other favourites finished in the same group as Dennis.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On the third stage, the race was neutralised following a major crash 58 km (36 mi) from the finish which put six of riders out of the race, including Cancellara.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The peloton continued to the final climb, the Mur de Huy, where Joaquim Rodríguez held off Froome to take the stage by one second.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Rodríguez was awarded the first the polka dot jersey as the leader of the mountains classification and Froome took the yellow, while also gaining time over the other general classification favourites.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] It was the third day in succession Martin ended in second place overall, and to three different riders.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The partially cobbled fourth stage saw Martin take the victory and the yellow jersey with an attack on the lead group 3 km (1.9 mi) from the finish in Cambrai.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On the fifth stage, a bunch sprint occurred and Greipel got the better of it by beating Peter Sagan and Mark Cavendish, respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] In the sixth stage, Zdeněk Štybar of Etixx–Quick-Step won after escaping on the concluding small ascent in the port city of Le Havre.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A crash in the final kilometre forced Martin to abandon the Tour with a broken collarbone, the second yellow jersey wearer to surrender after Cancellara.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A record was set after the stage, with Daniel Teklehaimanot becoming the first black African to lead the mountains classification.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Although Froome now led the race, no rider wore the yellow jersey on stage seven as Martin had finished the stage and earned the right to wear it.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Cavendish won the seventh from a bunch sprint in Fougères, Brittany.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome was awarded the yellow jersey after the stage.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage eight, finishing atop the Mûr-de-Bretagne, saw the first French victory of the Tour, with AG2R La Mondiale rider Alexis Vuillermoz launching an attack inside the final kilometre to take the victory.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The general classification favourites finished together except Vincenzo Nibali who lost ten seconds.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] BMC Racing Team won stage nine's team time trial by one second over Team Sky.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The squad of Nairo Quintana, Movistar Team, came in third, four seconds in arrears.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Alberto Contador's Tinkoff–Saxo in fourth, twenty-eight seconds down, and Nibali's Astana following, a further seven seconds behind.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The first rest day took place the following day in Pau.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage ten was the race's first arrival at altitude with the finish at La Pierre Saint-Martin in the Pyrenees.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The day's breakaway was caught and passed on the final climb by a select group.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome attacked with 6.4 km (4 mi) remaining to take the win, with teammate Richie Porte and Quintana a minute in arrears.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The stage saw time gaps open up across the general classification leaders.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The biggest loser was Nibali, who came in twenty-first, over four minutes behind Froome, who increased his lead to second placed Tejay van Garderen to two minutes and fifty-two seconds.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome took the polka dot jersey and Greipel the green.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage eleven was another mountainous stage; it was won by Rafał Majka (Tinkoff–Saxo), who was part of the early breakaway and attacked on the slopes of the Col du Tourmalet.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He soloed across the line in Cauterets one minute ahead of second-placed Dan Martin (Cannondale–Garmin).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Rodríguez gained his second victory of the race on stage twelve; he was part of an early twenty-two rider breakaway that reached the final climb to Plateau de Beille.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage thirteen saw the escapees being brought inside the one kilometre to go marker (known as the *flamme rouge*).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Greg Van Avermaet of BMC Racing Team took the uphill victory ahead of the chasing Sagan.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On stage fourteen, a twenty-four rider breakaway reached the final climb, the Côte de la Croix Neuve.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] After the breakaway had fractured, Thibaut Pinot and Romain Bardet led over the summit, before Steve Cummings of MTN–Qhubeka overtook them to take the victory at Brenoux Airport on the plateau above Mende.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Sagan was part of the breakaway, amassing maximum points at the intermediate sprint.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Over four minutes after Cummings had finished, Froome outsprinted Quintana while the other general classification favourites were slightly distanced.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Quintana moved into second place overall, displacing Van Garderen.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage fifteen had for principal difficulty the Col de l'Escrinet climb, which saw most of the sprinters succeeding at passing the climb in the lead group, with the notable exception of Cavendish.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Greipel won his third stage of the Tour, followed by John Degenkolb and Alexander Kristoff, respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On the next stage, featuring the Col de Manse as the final climb, Rubén Plaza (Lampre–Merida) escaped the leading group of breakaway riders on the ascent.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Sagan chased him down the descent, but to no avail as Plaza soloed to victory in Gap.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The next day was the second rest day, spent in Gap.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Stage seventeen, the first of four Alpine stages, saw third placed overall Van Garderen withdraw from the race with illness.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The stage was won by Team Giant–Alpecin's Simon Geschke, who escaped from the breakaway with under 50 km (31 mi) remaining to win in Pra-Loup.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Fifth placed overall Contador crashed on the descent of the Col d'Allos, losing over two minutes to race leader Froome.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On stage eighteen, Bardet attacked the breakaway close to the summit of the Col du Glandon and opened a gap on descent before riding solo to victory in Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Bardet moved up to tenth overall and became joint first with Rodríguez in the mountains classification, displacing Froome.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] In the Tour's queen stage, nineteenth, Nibali broke away from the general classification group close to the summit of the Col de la Croix de Fer to bridge and pass the breakaway group and win at La Toussuire - Les Sybelles.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Quintana came in second, forty-four seconds later, with Froome coming in a further thirty.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] In the Tour's penultimate stage, a select group of riders attacked on the Col de la Croix de Fer and made it to the finish on Alpe d'Huez, where they met the disintegrate early breakaway.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Pinot attacked passed the breakaways to take the victory ahead of the encroaching Quintana, who came in second after attacking the chasing general classification group on the Alpe.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Quintana gained a margin of eighty seconds over Froome, but it was not enough and had to settle for second place overall.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The final stage in Paris was won by Greipel, his fourth victory of this year's Tour.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome finished the race to claim his second Tour de France, becoming the first British rider to win the race on two occasions.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] He beat second-placed Quintana by seventy-two seconds, with his Movistar Team teammate Alejandro Valverde third.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Froome also claimed the mountains classification, the first time a rider had won both since Eddy Merckx in 1970.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Although he failed to win any stages during the race, Sagan won his fourth consecutive points classification with a total of 432, 66 ahead of Greipel in second.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The best young rider was Quintana, followed by Bardet and Team Giant–Alpecin's Warren Barguil, respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Movistar Team finished as the winners of the team classification, over fifty-seven minutes ahead of second-placed Team Sky.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Of the 198 starters, 160 reached the finish of the last stage in Paris.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] There were four main individual classifications contested in the 2015 Tour de France, as well as a team competition.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Time bonuses (time subtracted) returned to the Tour for the first time since the 2008 edition.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] For all stage finishes, excluding the two time trial stages, the three first finishers of stages earned bonuses of 10, 6 and 4 seconds respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Rain on the final stage forced the final times of the general classification to be taken on the first crossing of the finish line before the ten laps of the cobbled Champs-Élysées.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Riders were required to cross the finish line on the final lap to receive their times.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Riders received points for finishing among the highest placed in a stage finish, or in intermediate sprints during the stage.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A stage win was worth 50 points instead of 45, second place awarded 30 instead of 35 and third 20 instead of 30.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The sprint points rule change aimed to make a stage win more valuable.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The new system was in effect only on the Tour's six stages classified as flat (stages 2, 5, 6, 7, 15 and 21).
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] On seven stages (the cobble stage and six hillier stages, namely stages 3, 4, 8, 10, 13, 14 and 16) the rider who won received 30 points, 25 for the second rider, and so on.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] For the mountain stages (stages 11, 12, 17, 18, 19, 20) and the individual time trial (stage 1), the winner received 20 points.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] No points were awarded for the team time trial on stage nine.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Points were awarded to the riders that reached the summit of the most difficult climbs first.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The climbs were categorised as fourth-, third-, second-, first-category and *hors catégorie*, with the more difficult climbs rated lower.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Double points were awarded on the summit finishes on stages 10, 12, 17, 19 and 20.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] This was calculated the same way as the general classification, but the classification was restricted to riders who were born on or after 1 January 1990.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] This was calculated using the finishing times of the best three riders per team on each stage, excluding the team time trial; the leading team was the team with the lowest cumulative time.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The riders in the team that lead this classification were identified with yellow number bibs on the back of their jerseys and yellow helmets.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] No combativity awards were given for the time trials and the final stage.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] At the conclusion of the Tour, Romain Bardet won the overall super-combativity award, again, decided by a jury.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] A total of €2,030,150 was awarded in cash prizes in the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The overall winner of the general classification received €450,000, with the second and third placed riders got €200,000 and €100,000 respectively.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] All finishers of the race were awarded with money.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The holders of the classifications benefited on each stage they led; the final winners of the points and mountains were given €25,000, while the best young rider and most combative rider got €20,000.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Team prizes were available, with €10,000 for the winner of team time trial and €50,000 for the winners of the team classification. €8,000 was given to the winners of each stage of the race.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Due to a route change the Souvenir Henri Desgrange was replaced with the Col d'Allos in stage seventeen.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Rafał Majka won the Jacques Goddet and Simon Geschke won the Henri Desgrange.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Riders from the WorldTeams competing individually, as well as for their teams and nations, for points that contributed towards the World Tour rankings.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] The 238 points accrued by Chris Froome moved him up to second in the individual ranking, behind Alejandro Valverde.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] Despite Movistar Team's strong showing, Team Sky took over the lead of the team ranking due to Froome's points.
[src:abbeville/2015-tour-de-france] With three riders in the top ten, Spain remained the leaders of the nation ranking.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It is the *chef-lieu* of one of the arrondissements of Somme.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Located on the river Somme, it was the capital of Ponthieu.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is located on the river Somme, 20 km (12 mi) from its modern mouth in the English Channel.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The majority of the town is located on the east bank of the Somme, as well as on an island.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It is located at the head of the Abbeville Canal, and is 45 km (28 mi) northwest of Amiens and approximately 200 kilometres (120 mi) from Paris.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It is also 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) as the crow flies from the Baie de Somme and the English Channel.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the medieval period, it was the lowest crossing point on the Somme and it was nearby that Edward III's army crossed shortly before the Battle of Crécy in 1346.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Just halfway between Rouen and Lille, it is the historical capital of the County of Ponthieu and maritime Picardy.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville station is served by trains on the line between Boulogne-sur-Mer and Amiens and between Calais and Paris.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the southern terminus of the Réseau des Bains de Mer, the line to Dompierre-sur-Authie opened on 19 June 1892 and closed on 10 March 1947.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is located just near the A16 autoroute, and is about 1 hour 50 minutes by car from Paris.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville has an oceanic climate due to its proximity to the ocean.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The summers and winters are temperate and rainy, days of snow are fairly common (18 days of snow per year on average).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] There are 26 days of storm per year with a maximum in the months of July and August, the rains are frequent and distributed regularly in the year with precipitation totalling 781.3 millimetres (30.76 in) and 128 days with precipitation.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The highest temperature was 37.8 °C (100.0 °F) on 1 July 1952 and the record low is −17.4 °C (0.7 °F), which occurred during a particularly cold spell on 17 January 1985.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Its inhabitants are called *Abbevillois* in French.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The population of the commune is relatively old.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville is the seat of the Chambre de commerce et d'industrie d'Abbeville – Picardie maritime.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It manages ports, the aerodrome and industrial areas of the arrondissement of Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville manufactured textiles, and in particular, linens and tablecloths when the Van Robais family created la Manufacture Royale des Rames in 1665; however after the Edict of Nantes was revoked and the subsequent migration of Protestants away from the area, the cloth business succumbed.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Also affecting the economy of the town was the closure of the river port on the Somme River due to excessive silt.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It also has cordage factories, carpet factories, and spinning mills.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was awarded three flowers in 2007 by the *Conseil des Villes et Villages Fleuris de France* [Council of Floral Cities and Villages of France] in the Contest of floral cities and villages.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville has featured as the departure point for Stage 4 of the 2012 Tour de France and the departure point for Stage 1 of the 2011 Tour de Picardie.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The commune has also been on the route of the Grand Prix de la Somme one-day cycle race.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville will feature as the departure point for Stage 6 of the 2015 Tour de France, on 9 July.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Victor Hugo evoked the trips he made to Abbeville in his accounts of travel.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Collegiate Church of Saint-Vulfran is portrayed in the short story "Casting the Runes," by M.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] James, as the site of a mysterious death.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] André Maurois, in *Les Silences du Colonel Bramble* (1918) amusingly described the intact commercial spirit of the inhabitants of Abbeville in the last months of the war.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Maurois' *Ni ange ni bete* (Neither Angel, Nor Beast) is also set in Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Christian Morel de Sarcus, in his novel *Déluges*, Éditions Henry, November 2004 (2005 Prix Renaissance), evokes the bombing of 1940 and the floods of the Somme of 2001.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Romans occupied it and named it *Abbatis Villa*.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] There are also *Hableville* in 1607 and *Ableville* in 1643, with transitional addition of an L.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville boasted of having never been taken and was called *Abbeville la pucelle* ("the virgin").
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It was also granted many privileges from the Capetian kings, to reward its loyalty.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The blason populaire of the people of Abbeville is *"chés bourgeois d'Adville"*.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the capital of the former province of Ponthieu.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Today, it is one of the three sub-prefectures of the Somme department.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The commune is part of the Communauté d'agglomération de la Baie de Somme of which it has the headquarters.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The subsoil contains many vestiges of the Pleistocene.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] This discovery was a founding element of prehistory as a science.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The name Abbeville has been adopted to name a category of Paleolithic stone tools.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] These stone tools are also known as handaxes.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Various handaxes were found near Abbeville by Jacques Boucher de Perthes starting in 1838 and he was the first to describe the stones in detail, pointing out in the first publication of its kind, in 1846, that the stones were chipped deliberately by early man, so as to form a tool.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Some of these artifacts are displayed at the Musee Boucher-de-Perthes.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] A more refined and later version of handaxe production was found in the Abbeville/Somme River district.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The more refined handaxe became known as the Acheulean industry, named after Saint-Acheul, today a suburb of Amiens.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It retained some importance into the Bronze Age.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Although the research of Jacques Boucher de Perthes has highlighted an occupation of the site of Abbeville (*Menchecourt-les-Abbeville* quarter) from the Acheulean era, in Roman times it was a succession of marshes, similar to marsh of *Saint-Gilles* which remains today.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Further to the north, the entire plateau between the Authie and the Somme was covered in primary forest.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Romans had to break through this forest massif for the passage of the road from Amiens to the village of Ponches on the one hand, and on the other to the west by the road linking the Beauvaisis in Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The couple Abbeville / Saint-Valery-sur-Somme is the key to the historical enigma of the landing of Magnus Maximus and his Britto-Roman troops in the spring of 383 AD (St-Valery = Leuconos > Pors Liogan; Abbeville = Talence > Tolente).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The road to Paris passes near the Vieux-Rouen-sur-Bresle, which has been identified with the character Himbaldus (Château-Hubault).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the 7th century, the Benedictine monks of Saint-Valéry, Saint-Josse, Saint-Saulve de Montreuil, Forest-Montiers, Balance and Valloires cleared the woods that were close to their monasteries.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Frankish king Dagobert I then gave part of the forest of Crécy, the hermitage became the Abbey of Saint-Riquier: it is the Act of birth of the abbatial field of Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The name, Abbeville, comes from the Latin and means "*town* (or more exactly) *field of Abbots*" (of Saint-Riquier).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The first historical mention of Abbeville, in the chronicle of Hariulf, dates to 831 AD.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It was a small island in the Somme, inhabited by fishermen who took refuge there with their boats and had fortified it against barbarian invasions from the north.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Abbot Angilbert built a castle to defend this island, which depended on the Abbey of Saint-Riquier.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It was an important fort city responsible for the defense of the Somme.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 992, Hugh Capet fortified the city and gave it to his daughter, Gisèle, on her marriage to Hugh I, Count of Ponthieu who resided in Montreuil.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] From the 12th century, the Abbot opened a leprosy hospice, the *maladrerie des Frères du Val*, moved to Grand-Laviers in the following century, before urban sprawl.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Then accessible to boats, Abbeville became a port of the English Channel under the dependence of the Abbots of Saint-Riquier.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Subsequently, the silting up of the Bay of Somme forced the sea to recede by 12 kilometres (7.5 mi), but the city continued to be a trading port.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville became the capital of the Ponthieu and rapidly spread on both banks of the River Somme, right on the slope of the hillsides and left into the marshes.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1095, Guy I Count of Ponthieu founded the Abbey Saint-Pierre of Abbeville and on 24 May 1098, he was dubbed as a Knight by Louis the Fat.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On the occasion of the First Crusade, Abbeville was the meeting point of many troops from the northern provinces.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Godefroy de Bouillon reviewed them on the current location of the Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] To commemorate the event, they built a belfry in 1126.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] A century later, Jeanne de Dammartin, Countess of Ponthieu (1220–1278), allowed the religious to convert an additional part of forests into cropland, allowing the development of the local economy.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Afterwards it was governed by the Counts of Ponthieu.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Together with that county, it came into the possession of the Alençon and other French families, and afterwards into that of the House of Castile.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1214, the Abbeville militia took part in the Battle of Bouvines.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the middle of the 13th century, Abbeville was "one of the best cities of the Kings of France".
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Its port was one of the first of the Kingdom and its considerable trade.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1259, the Estates-General of the Kingdom stood at Abbeville and Henry III of England has met with Louis IX of France to sign the Treaty of Paris, which settled the question of the conquests of Philip Augustus.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1272, Ponthieu with Abbeville, passed by marriage to the kings of England, but Philip V took over the city, claiming that Edward II of England had not fulfilled its duty of vassal.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Edward II complied with the feudal law, and Abbeville fell under English rule.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] However many challenges rose between the bourgeois and their new masters.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Throughout the Hundred Years' War, the town was alternately occupied by English and French forces, causing the inhabitants of the town enormous suffering.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] They were tested by excessive taxes and terrible epidemics.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Over the decades, the region was devastated by looting, epidemics and wolves.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The city thus appealed to the King of France twice, in 1406 and in 1415.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Affected by the English expedition of 1346, Abbeville resisted the English army, and served as a home base for Jean Marant who refuelled Calais besieged by the English.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1360, it was transferred, with the County of Ponthieu of which it was the capital, to the Crown of England by the Treaty of Brétigny.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] That same year, John II of France stayed there after returning from captivity.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1361, Abbeville, again English, poorly welcomed its new masters.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Ringois, a bourgeois of the city, refusing to take the oath of obedience to Edward III of England, was taken to English soil and hurled from the top of the Tower of Dover Castle into the sea in 1368.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During this period, a revolt of Jacques was defeated by the Abbeville militia in the vicinity of Saint-Riquier.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The soldiers of Charles V captured the city by surprise, but the English recaptured it shortly after and it remained in their possession until 1385.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Like other Picardy cities, it then passed under Burgundian rule at the end of the Battle of Mons-en-Vimeu in 1421.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1430, Henry VI of England was received at Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1435, the city was ceded to Philip the Good, the Duke of Burgundy, by the Treaty of Arras.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Louis XI bought Abbeville from Philip the Good in 1463 and visited the city on 27 September of the same year.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In December, by letters patent, he confirmed the privileges of the city, attached by his predecessors, but in 1465 Charles the Bold revoked the grant by taking the lead of the League of the Public Weal.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1466, the municipality enacted safety regulations recommending to reduce or not use flammable materials (such as walls in timber or straw roofs) in construction, in order to reduce the risk of fire.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] However, it clashed with general hostility, and the regulations were finally just applied.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Louis XI failed before Abbeville in 1471, but recovered Picardy on the death of the Duke of Burgundy in 1477.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1477 it was annexed by King Louis XI, and was held by two illegitimate branches of the royal family in the 16th and 17th centuries, being in 1696 reunited to the crown.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1480, then 1483, a plague epidemic ravaged Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 3 October 1514, Louis XII married Mary Tudor in Abbeville, the daughter of Henry VII of England.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 23 June 1517, Francis I came to Abbeville with the Queen and met Cardinal Wolsey, representing the King of England, to form a league against Charles V.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1523, the English finally fell alongside Charles V in the wars of Francis I and the city had to suffer many frequent requisitions.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] That same year, an outbreak of plague ravaged Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] A further epidemic of plague struck Abbeville in 1582.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1531, Francis I performed a new tour in the city.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The most serious blows to Abbeville were the series of English raids by the Duke of Suffolk on the sides of the estuary in 1544, after the fall of Boulogne and Montreuil.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] King Henry II was received in Abbeville in 1550.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During the Wars of Religion, the Protestant governor was massacred with his family, by the people.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1568, François Cocqueville, a Protestant leader of war, entered the Ponthieu with 3,000 soldiers.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] He plundered and sacked the Abbey of Dommartin, towns, churches and castles of Authie and Saint-Valery-sur-Somme region.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Chased by the Marshal de Brissac, Cocqueville was captured with several of his own and they were beheaded in the marketplace of Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Bartholomew's Day massacre caused no casualties in Abbeville due to the moderation of Léonor d'Orléans, the Duke of Longueville and governor of Picardy.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] However, Abbeville had embraced the Catholic League and suffered from the Wars of Religion0, and it was relieved when it was recognised, by Henry IV in April 1594, despite the clergy who persisted in its resistance.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Following this, on 18 December 1594, the King of France Henry IV visited Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] At the beginning of the 17th century a plague epidemic wreaked havoc.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] More than 8,000 people perished, thus depopulating Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 21 December 1620, King Louis XIII visited the town.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] His sister Henrietta went there several times.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1635 and 1636 the town suffered from the war against the Holy Roman Empire and Spain.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] They destroyed many villages located in the surrounding area.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Richelieu stayed in the city in October.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] A plague epidemic raged again during the years 1635, 1636 and 1637.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1656, 6,000 soldiers, who had participated in the English Civil War, landed in France and took their quarters in Abbeville from where they left to go and reinforce the army of Turenne en route to Valenciennes.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Shortly after, Balthazar de Fargues sold the place to John of Austria and after meeting the price, he refused to deliver it to him, raising troops for himself who were then spread throughout the Ponthieu to ransom the inhabitants.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Finally stopped, he was tried and hanged at *Place Saint-Pierre* on 17 March 1665.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1657, Louis XIV came twice to Abbeville with his mother, Anne of Austria.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] By the mid-16th century, the woad trade shrank after the promotion of the pastel of the Pays du Midi, and it took to restructuring crafts.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Colbert used it, and under Louis XIV, the city developed through the installation of Van Robais, manufacturers of sheets and tapestries from the Netherlands who, in 1665, created the Manufacture royale des Rames (drapery workshops).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1685, it suffered a serious blow at the Revocation of the Edict of Nantes, the Protestant temple was destroyed and the persecuted workers who were the majority of skilled labour left the town, including those of Van Robais.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The population decreased very strongly and never fully recovered from this exodus of talent.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1693 Ponthieu became the refuge of a considerable number of Bretons and Normans who had left their country because of famine, but they almost all perished of misery.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] At the end of the reign of Louis XIV the country was covered with troops.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1708, after the capture of Lille, the troops of the Duke of Marlborough and Eugene of Savoy came forward frequently at the gates of Abbeville, ransoming the farms and villages.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The winter of 1709 was terrible; people perished from cold, hunger and misery.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] At this time industry was quite dark and the State was required to help sheets manufacturers.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1717, Russian monarch Peter the Great passed through Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In July 1766, the Chevalier de La Barre, accused of having, a year earlier, failed to give a due salute to a religious procession for Corpus Christi by refusing to remove his hat and singing ungodly songs.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] However, the story is more complex and revolves around a mutilated cross.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] He was executed on the *Place du Grand-Marché* for blasphemy.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Subject to the issue, his legs were crushed.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The right hand and the determined language, his decapitated corpse was finally delivered to the flames with the *Dictionnaire philosophique* of Voltaire on the same place.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Today, a paving stone, engraved with his name and the date of his execution, is visible on the place of execution (*Place Max-Lejeune*), near the town hall.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The martyrdom of the Chevalier de La Barre served as Voltaire's banner in his fight against religious fanaticism.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 2 November 1773, the powder magazine exploded killing 150 people and damaging nearly 1,000 houses.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Administratively, the people of Abbeville formed a subdelegation whose competence has been confused with that of the delegation of the same name (located in the Generalitat of Amiens).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On the eve of the Revolution, Abbeville was the chef-lieu of a main electoral Bailiwick (without secondary Bailiwick).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was fairly important in the 18th century, when the Van Robais Royal Manufacture (one of the first major factories in France) brought great prosperity (but some class controversy) to the town.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] There were no significant excesses during periods of Revolution and the Terror.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1793, on *Place Saint-Pierre* the furniture of the churches was burned, along with images and the feudal titles.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Church of Saint-vulfran became the Temple of Reason.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 8 June 1794, a festival was celebrated in honour of the Supreme Being.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville suffered from famine in 1794 and 1795.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 5 January 1795, the Hotel of Grutuze, built under Charles VII, attended by the directors of the district, was destroyed by a fire.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1797, the Society of Emulation of Abbeville, one of the oldest learned societies of France, was created.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1798 and 1799, the winter was severe and a part of the town was flooded.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 18 brumaire year X (9 November 1801), there was a terrible hurricane that caused more than 1,300,000 francs worth of damage in the arrondissement.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 29 prairial year XI (18 June 1803), Napoleon passed through the town for the first time.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During the preparations of the expedition he was planning against the United Kingdom, the First Consul often spent time in Abbeville by going to the camp of Boulogne.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1813, as part of the reorganisation of the cavalry which had been decimated in Russia, the arrondissement offered the government 43 men mounted and equipped.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Early in 1814, with invasion becoming more imminent every day, the urban National Guard was reorganised across the whole of the Empire.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] 30 pieces of artillery were placed on the walls, and to complete the defense system, trees were felled in the vicinity to make 30,000 palisades and 14,000 shields.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 20 February, a column of cavalry forming the vanguard of the 3rd Corps of the Prussian army, commanded by Baron de Geismar, arrived in Doullens, before heading to Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Immediately, the Abbevillois ran to arms.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] 800 rifles were made available and a vigorous resistance began when the population learned that this supposed vanguard of the Prussian army had more than 1,500 to 2,000 men in its ranks, both Cossacks and Saxon Lancers, who eventually made their way to Paris.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In early April, after the Battle of Paris and the abdication of Napoleon, 2,000 Lancers and Prussian cuirassiers commanded by General Röder arrived from Paris and the surrounding countryside, and committed all kinds of excesses during their stay.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 27 April 1814, Louis XVIII entered the town and was received with an outpouring of joy.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During the First Restoration, many distinguished people and about 10,000 British troops passed through Abbeville, to return to their country.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The Duke of Berry, accompanied by the 10th Regiment of Cuirassiers and the 108th Infantry Regiment, stayed there.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 21 March 1815, King Louis XVIII, who was on the way to exile, spent a night in the town.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1815, after the Battle of Waterloo, the town was again put into defence.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] However, after numerous desertions, the garrison was reduced to 400 men.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Victor Hugo came to Abbeville three times, as a tourist: In 1835, he stayed there successively from 26 July (after going down to *L'Écu de Brabant*), then on 4 and 5 August (staying at *L'Hôtel d'Angleterre*).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In August and September 1837, he came to Amiens after having descended the Somme by Steamboat.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Finally, in 1849, leaving the city in the rain on 11 September.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1847, there was the arrival of the railway in Abbeville with the opening of the Amiens-Abbeville section of the line of the Longueau–Boulogne railway.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1856, the Abbeville railway station was inaugurated, which is still in service.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville was the birthplace of Rear Admiral Amédée Courbet (1827–1885), whose victories on land and at sea made him a national hero during the Sino-French War (August 1884 to April 1885).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Courbet died in June 1885, shortly after the end of the war, at Makung in the Pescadores Islands, and his body was brought back to France and buried in Abbeville on 1 September 1885 after a state funeral at Les Invalides a few days earlier.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Abbeville's old Haymarket Square (Place du Marché-au-Blé) was renamed Place de l'Amiral Courbet in July 1885, shortly after the news of Courbet's death reached France, and an extravagant baroque statue of Courbet was erected in the middle of the square at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] The statue was damaged in a devastating German bombing raid during World War II.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It was an allied base during World War I.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 13 August 1892, the Ortiz gang committed a burglary there.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1896, the Socialist Jules Guesde came to lecture in Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the aftermath, a group of the French Workers' Party and a House of the people are created.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] 1899, the phone has already arrived in Abbeville but its operation does not any satisfaction.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1899, Abbeville industry had a mill, a table linen factory, a rope factory, a factory of weight scales, three smelters, a boiler works, a locksmith for buildings, a wood grinding mill, a distillery, etc.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 7 July 1907 was the inauguration of the La Barre Monument, gathering many Republicans, delegates from Socialist groups and free-thinkers.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During World War I, the town was never occupied by the German troops (as evidenced by the monument built on the Mont de Caubert).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1916, during the Battle of the Somme, it served as a military hospital (the 3rd Australian General Hospital).
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] As with Amiens and Beauvais, the town was partially destroyed and the aftermath of war is significant nearby, particularly due to unexploded ordnance still found in the soil.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In 1918, it was the seat of two Anglo-French conferences (conferences of Abbeville): That of 25 March, between Field Marshal Haig and Generals Wilson and Foch, who convened the Doullens conference.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] During the second conference on 2 May, Foch demanded authority on the Italian front but only obtained a power of coordination.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] It was at the Conference of Abbeville (1 and 2 May 1918) while the armies weakened that Foch opposite Clemenceau and Lloyd George would have considered a fallback to the south to protect the capital.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the event that the French and British armies were separated and they could no longer defend both access to the ports of the English Channel and Paris, the British army would have then withdrawn and stood on the Somme.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 31 May 1918, American war poet John Allan Wyeth was a Second Lieutenant in the 33rd U.S.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Infantry Division, which was largely composed of soldiers from the Illinois Army National Guard.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Wyeth and his fellow Doughboys were stationed in nearby Huppy, when German aeroplanes began a bombing raid on Abbeville.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] At the time, such air raids were a nightly affair and Abbeville was in the process of being evacuated.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] Wyeth later versified his memories of the air raid in the sonnet *Huppy*.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 3 May 1936, voters in the 1st District of Abbeville did not derogate from a broad popular movement.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] In the 2nd round, they chose Max Lejeune as the MP who, at 27 years old, was the youngest elected to the chamber.
[src:abbeville/abbeville-p01] On 12 September 1939 the Abbeville Conference took place in which France and the United Kingdom decided to not continue the attack on Germany, which resulted in a tougher situation on eastern front.
